# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gail-ashley
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists study human prehistory and history, from the development of the first stone tools at Lomekwi in East Africa 3.3 million years ago up until recent decades.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is distinct from palaeontology, which is the study of fossil remains.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is particularly important for learning about prehistoric societies, for which, by definition, there are no written records.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Prehistory includes over 99% of the human past, from the Paleolithic until the advent of literacy in societies around the world.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology has various goals, ranging from understanding culture history to reconstructing past lifeways to documenting and explaining changes in human societies over time.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Derived from Greek, the term *archaeology* means "the study of ancient history".
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology developed out of antiquarianism in Europe during the 19th century and has since become a discipline practiced worldwide.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Nation-states have used archaeology to create particular visions of the past.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Since its early development, various specific sub-disciplines of archaeology have developed, including maritime archaeology, feminist archaeology, and archaeoastronomy, and numerous different scientific techniques have been developed to aid archaeological investigation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Nonetheless, today, archaeologists face many problems, such as dealing with pseudoarchaeology, the looting of artifacts, a lack of public interest, and opposition to the excavation of human remains.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In Ancient Mesopotamia, a foundation deposit of the Akkadian Empire ruler Naram-Sin (ruled c.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] 2200 BC) was discovered and analysed by king Nabonidus, c.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] 550 BC, who is thus known as the first archaeologist.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He was also the first to date an archaeological artifact in his attempt to date Naram-Sin's temple during his search for it.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Even though his estimate was inaccurate by about 1,500 years, it was still a very good one considering the lack of accurate dating technology at the time.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The science of archaeology (from Greek ἀρχαιολογία *archaiologia*, from ἀρχαῖος, *arkhaios* 'ancient' and -λογία, *-logia* 'study') grew out of the older multi-disciplinary study known as antiquarianism.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians studied history with particular attention to ancient artifacts, manuscripts, and historical sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Antiquarianism focused on the empirical evidence available for understanding the past, encapsulated in the motto of the 18th century antiquary Richard Colt Hoare: "We speak from facts, not theory".
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Tentative steps towards the systematization of archaeology as a science took place during the Enlightenment period in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In Imperial China during the Song dynasty (960–1279), figures such as Ouyang Xiu and Zhao Mingcheng established the tradition of Chinese epigraphy by investigating, preserving, and analyzing ancient Chinese bronze inscriptions from the Shang and Zhou periods.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Such antiquarian pursuits waned after the Song period, were revived in the 17th century during the Qing dynasty, but were always considered a branch of Chinese historiography rather than a separate discipline of archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In Renaissance Europe, philosophical interest in the remains of Greco-Roman civilization and the rediscovery of classical culture began in the late Middle Ages, with humanism.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Cyriacus of Ancona was a restlessly itinerant Italian humanist and antiquarian who came from a prominent family of merchants in Ancona, a maritime republic on the Adriatic.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He noted down his archaeological discoveries in his diary, *Commentaria* (in six volumes).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Flavio Biondo, an Italian Renaissance humanist historian, created a systematic guide to the ruins and topography of ancient Rome in the early 15th century, for which he has been called an early founder of archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians of the 16th century, including John Leland and William Camden, conducted surveys of the English countryside, drawing, describing and interpreting the monuments that they encountered.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* first cites "archaeologist" in 1824; this soon became the usual term for one major branch of antiquarian activity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] "Archaeology", from 1607 onward, initially meant what we would call "ancient history" generally, with the narrower modern sense first seen in 1837.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Twelfth-century Indian scholar Kalhana's writings involved recording local traditions and examining manuscripts, inscriptions, coins, and architecture, which are described as among the earliest traces of archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] One of his notable works is called *Rajatarangini*, which was completed c.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] 1150 and is considered one of the first historical works of India.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Among the first sites to undergo archaeological excavation were Stonehenge and other megalithic monuments in England.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] John Aubrey (1626–1697) was a pioneer archaeologist who recorded numerous megalithic and other field monuments in southern England.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He was also ahead of his time in analysing his findings.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He attempted to chart the chronological stylistic evolution of handwriting, medieval architecture, costume, and shield-shapes.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Excavations were also carried out by the Spanish military engineer Roque Joaquín de Alcubierre in the ancient towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, both of which had been covered by ash during the Eruption of Mount Vesuvius in AD 79.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] These excavations began in 1748 in Pompeii and in 1738 in Herculaneum.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The discovery of entire towns, complete with utensils and even human shapes, as well as the unearthing of frescos, had a big impact throughout Europe.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] However, before the development of modern techniques, excavations tended to be haphazard; the importance of concepts such as stratification and context was overlooked.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the mid-18th century, the German Johann Joachim Winckelmann lived in Rome and devoted himself to the study of Roman antiquities, gradually acquiring an unrivalled knowledge of ancient art.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Then, he visited the archaeological excavations being conducted at Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He was one of the founders of scientific archaeology and first applied the categories of style on a large, systematic basis to the history of art.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He was one of the first to separate Greek art into periods and time classifications.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Winckelmann has been called both "The prophet and founding hero of modern archaeology" and the father of the discipline of art history.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The father of archaeological excavation was William Cunnington (1754–1810).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He undertook excavations in Wiltshire from around 1798, funded by Sir Richard Colt Hoare.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Cunnington made meticulous recordings of Neolithic and Bronze Age barrows, and the terms he used to categorize and describe them are still used by archaeologists today.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] President Thomas Jefferson also did his own excavations in 1784 using the trench method, on several Native American burial mounds in Virginia.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] His excavations were prompted by the "Moundbuilders" question; however, his careful methods led him to conclude that there was no reason why the ancestors of the Native Americans of his time could not have raised those mounds.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] One of the major achievements of 19th-century archaeology was the development of stratigraphy.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The idea of overlapping strata tracing back to successive periods was borrowed from the new geological and palaeontological work of scholars like William Smith, James Hutton, and Charles Lyell.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The systematic application of stratigraphy to archaeology first occurred during excavations of prehistorical and Bronze Age sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the third and fourth decades of the 19th century, archaeologists such as Jacques Boucher de Perthes and Christian Jürgensen Thomsen began to arrange the artifacts they had found in chronological order.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A major figure in the development of archaeology into a rigorous science was army officer and ethnologist Augustus Pitt Rivers, who began excavations on his land in England in the 1880s.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Highly methodical by the standards of the time, he is widely regarded as the first scientific archaeologist.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He arranged his artifacts by type or "Typology (archaeology)", and within types chronologically.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This style of arrangement, designed to highlight evolutionary trends in human artifacts, was of enormous significance for accurately dating the objects.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] His most important methodological innovation was his insistence that *all* artifacts, not just beautiful or unique ones, be collected and catalogued.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] William Flinders Petrie is another man who may legitimately be called the Father of Archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Petrie was the first to scientifically investigate the Great Pyramid in Egypt during the 1880s.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] He was also responsible for mentoring and training a whole generation of Egyptologists, including Howard Carter who went on to achieve fame with the discovery of the tomb of 14th-century BC pharaoh Tutankhamun.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The first stratigraphic excavation to gain wide public popularity was that of Hissarlik, on the site of ancient Troy, carried out by Heinrich Schliemann, Frank Calvert, and Wilhelm Dörpfeld in the 1870s.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] These scholars individuated nine different cities that had overlapped with one another, from prehistory to the Hellenistic period.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, the work of Sir Arthur Evans at Knossos in Crete revealed the ancient existence of an equally advanced Minoan civilization.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The next major figure in the development of archaeology was Sir Mortimer Wheeler, whose highly disciplined approach to excavation and systematic coverage in the 1920s and 1930s brought the science on swiftly.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Wheeler developed the grid system of excavation, which was further improved by his student Kathleen Kenyon.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology became a professional activity in the first half of the 20th century, and it became possible to study archaeology as a subject in universities and even schools.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] By the end of the 20th century, nearly all professional archaeologists, at least in developed countries, were graduates.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Further adaptation and innovation in archaeology continued in this period, when maritime archaeology and urban archaeology became more prevalent, and rescue archaeology was developed in response to increasing commercial development.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The purpose of archaeology is to learn more about past societies and the development of the human race.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Over 99% of human development has occurred within prehistoric cultures, which did not use writing; no written records exist for study.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Without such written sources, the only way to understand prehistoric societies is through archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Because archaeology is the study of past human activity, it stretches back to about 2.5 million years ago when the first stone tools were found – The Oldowan Industry.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Many important developments in human history occurred during prehistory, such as the evolution of humanity during the Paleolithic period, when the hominins developed from the australopithecines in Africa and eventually into modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology also sheds light on many of humanity's technological advances, for instance, the ability to use fire, the development of stone tools, the discovery of metallurgy, the beginnings of religion, and the creation of agriculture.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Without archaeology, little or nothing would be known about humanity's use of material culture that predates writing.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] However, it is not only prehistoric, pre-literate cultures that can be studied using archaeology; historic, literate cultures can also be studied through the sub-discipline of historical archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] For many literate cultures, such as Ancient Greece and Mesopotamia, their surviving records are often incomplete and biased to some extent.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In many societies, literacy was restricted to the elite classes, such as the clergy or the bureaucracy of the court or the temple.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The literacy of aristocrats has sometimes been restricted to deeds and contracts.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The interests and worldview of elites are often quite different from those of the populace.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Writings that were produced by people more representative of the general population were unlikely to find their way into libraries and be preserved there for posterity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Thus, written records tend to reflect the biases, assumptions, cultural values, and possibly deceptions of a limited range of individuals, usually a small fraction of the larger population.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Hence, written records cannot be trusted as a sole source.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The material record may be closer to a fair representation of society, though it is subject to its own biases, such as sampling bias and differential preservation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Often, archaeology provides the only means of learning about the existence and behavior of people in the past.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Over the millennia, many thousands of cultures and societies, and billions of people, have come and gone, with little or no written record, or with existing records that are misrepresentative or incomplete.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Writing, as it is known today, did not exist in human civilization until the 4th millennium BC, and even then, only in a relatively small number of technologically advanced civilizations.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In contrast, *Homo sapiens* has existed for at least 200,000 years, and other *Homo* species for millions of years (see Human evolution).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] These civilizations are, not coincidentally, the best known; they have been open to historical inquiry for centuries, whereas the study of prehistoric cultures has only recently emerged.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Within a literate civilization, many events and important human practices may not be officially recorded.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Any knowledge of the early years of human civilization – the development of agriculture, cult practices of folk religion, the rise of the first cities – must come from archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In addition to their scientific importance, archaeological remains sometimes have political or cultural significance for the descendants of the people who produced them, monetary value for collectors, or strong aesthetic appeal.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Many people identify archaeology with the recovery of such aesthetic, religious, political, or economic treasures rather than with the reconstruction of past societies.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This view is often espoused in works of popular fiction, such as Raiders of the Lost Ark, The Mummy, and King Solomon's Mines.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] When unrealistic subjects are treated more seriously, accusations of pseudoscience are invariably levelled at their proponents *(see Pseudoarchaeology)*.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] However, these endeavours, real and fictional, are not representative of modern archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] There is no single approach to archaeological theory adopted by all archaeologists.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the 1960s, an archaeological movement largely led by American archaeologists like Lewis Binford and Kent Flannery arose that rebelled against the established cultural-history archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] They proposed a "New Archaeology", which would be more "scientific" and "anthropological", with hypothesis testing and the scientific method very important parts of what became known as processual archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the 1980s, a new postmodern movement arose led by the British archaeologists Michael Shanks, Christopher Tilley, Daniel Miller, and Ian Hodder, which has become known as post-processual archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It questioned processualism's appeals to scientific positivism and impartiality; it emphasized the importance of a more self-critical theoretical reflexivity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] However, processualists have criticized this approach as lacking scientific rigour.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The validity of both processualism and post-processualism is still under debate.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, another theory, known as historical processualism, has emerged seeking to incorporate a focus on process and post-processual archaeology's emphasis on reflexivity and history.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] An archaeological investigation usually involves several distinct phases, each employing a variety of methods.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Before any practical work can begin, however, a clear objective for what the archaeologists are seeking to achieve must be agreed upon.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This done, a site is surveyed to learn as much as possible about it and its surroundings.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Second, an excavation may be conducted to uncover any buried archaeological features.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] And third, the information collected during the excavation is studied and evaluated to achieve the archaeologists' original research objectives.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It is then considered good practice for the information to be published so that it is available to other archaeologists and historians, although this is sometimes neglected.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Before actually starting to dig at a location, remote sensing can be used to identify where sites are located within a large area or to provide more information about sites or regions.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] There are two types of remote sensing instruments—passive and active.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments detect natural energy reflected or emitted by the observed scene.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments sense only radiation emitted by the object being viewed or reflected by the object from a source other than the instrument.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Active instruments emit energy and record the reflections.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Satellite imagery is an example of passive remote sensing.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The distance to the object is determined by recording the time between the transmitted and backscattered pulses and using the speed of light to calculate the distance travelled.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Lidars can determine atmospheric profiles of aerosols, clouds, and other atmospheric constituents.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The archaeological project then continues (or begins) with a field survey.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A regional survey is an attempt to locate previously unknown sites within a region systematically.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A site survey is an attempt to systematically locate features of interest, such as houses and middens, within a site.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Each of these two goals may be accomplished with largely the same methods.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Surveys were not widely practised in the early days of archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Cultural historians and earlier researchers were usually content to discover the locations of monumental sites from the local populace and to excavate only the plainly visible features there.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Gordon Willey pioneered the technique of regional settlement pattern survey in 1949 in the Viru Valley of coastal Peru, and survey of all levels became prominent with the rise of processual archaeology some years later.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Survey work has many benefits if performed as a preliminary exercise to, or even in place of, excavation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It requires relatively little time and expense because it does not involve processing large volumes of soil to search for artifacts.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] (Nevertheless, surveying a large region or site can be expensive, so archaeologists often employ sampling methods.) As with other forms of non-destructive archaeology, survey avoids ethical issues (of particular concern to descendant peoples) associated with destroying a site through excavation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It is the only way to gather some forms of information, such as settlement patterns and settlement structure.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Survey data are commonly assembled into maps, which may show surface features and/or artifact distribution.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The simplest survey technique is a surface survey.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It involves combing an area, usually on foot but sometimes using mechanized transport, to search for features or artifacts visible on the surface.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Surface survey cannot detect sites or features that are completely buried under earth or overgrown with vegetation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Surface survey may also include mini-excavation techniques such as augers, corers, and shovel test pits.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] If no materials are found, the area surveyed is deemed sterile.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey is conducted using cameras attached to airplanes, balloons, UAVs, or even Kites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A bird's-eye view is useful for quick mapping of large or complex sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs are used to document the status of the archaeological dig.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Aerial imaging can also detect many things not visible from the surface.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Plants growing above a buried human-made structure, such as a stone wall, will develop more slowly, while those above other types of features (such as middens) may develop more rapidly.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Photographs of ripening grain, which changes colour rapidly at maturation, have revealed buried structures with great precision.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs taken at different times of day will help show the outlines of structures by changes in shadows.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey also employs ultraviolet, infrared, ground-penetrating radar wavelengths, Lidar and thermography.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Geophysical survey can be the most effective way to see beneath the ground.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Magnetometers detect minute deviations in the Earth's magnetic field caused by iron artifacts, kilns, some types of stone structures, and even ditches and middens.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Devices that measure the electrical resistivity of the soil are also widely used.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeological features whose electrical resistivity contrasts with that of surrounding soils can be detected and mapped.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Some archaeological features (such as those composed of stone or brick) have higher resistivity than typical soils.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In comparison, others (such as organic deposits or unfired clay) tend to have lower resistivity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Although some archaeologists consider the use of metal detectors to be tantamount to treasure hunting, others deem them an effective tool in archaeological surveying.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Examples of formal archaeological use of metal detectors include musketball distribution analysis on English Civil War battlefields, metal distribution analysis before excavation of a 19th-century ship wreck, and service cable location during evaluation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Metal detectorists have also contributed to archaeology, where they have made detailed records of their results and refrained from raising artifacts from their archaeological context.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the UK, metal detectorists have been invited to participate in the Portable Antiquities Scheme.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Regional survey in underwater archaeology uses geophysical or remote sensing devices such as a marine magnetometer, side-scan sonar, or sub-bottom sonar.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeological excavation has existed even when the field was still the domain of amateurs, and it remains the primary source of data recovered in most field projects.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It can reveal several types of information that are usually not accessible through surveys, such as stratigraphy, three-dimensional structure, and verifiably primary context.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Modern excavation techniques require that the precise locations of objects and features, known as their provenance or provenience, be recorded.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This always involves determining their horizontal locations and, sometimes, their vertical positions as well (see also Primary Laws of Archaeology).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Likewise, their association, or relationship with nearby objects and features, needs to be recorded for later analysis.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This allows the archaeologist to deduce which artifacts and features were likely used together and which may be from different phases of activity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] For example, excavation of a site reveals its stratigraphy; if a succession of distinct cultures occupied a site, artifacts from more recent cultures will lie above those from earlier ones.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Excavation is the most expensive phase of archaeological research, in relative terms.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Also, as a destructive process, it carries ethical concerns.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] As a result, very few sites are excavated in their entirety.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Again, the percentage of a site excavated depends greatly on the country and the "method statement" issued.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Sampling is even more important in excavation than in survey.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Sometimes large mechanical equipment, such as backhoes (JCBs), is used in excavation, especially to remove the topsoil (overburden), though this method is increasingly used with great caution.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Following this rather dramatic step, the exposed area is usually hand-cleaned with trowels or hoes to ensure that all features are apparent.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The next task is to create a site plan and then use it to help determine the excavation method.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Features dug into the natural subsoil are normally excavated in portions to produce a visible archaeological section for recording.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A feature, for example, a pit or a ditch, consists of two parts: the cut and the fill.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The cut describes the edge of the feature where it meets the natural soil.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The fill is what the feature is filled with, and will often appear quite distinct from the natural soil.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The cut and fill are given consecutive numbers for recording purposes.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Scaled plans and sections of individual features are all drawn on site; black-and-white and colour photographs of them are taken; and recording sheets are filled in, describing the context of each feature.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] All this information serves as a permanent record of the now-destroyed archaeology and is used to describe and interpret the site.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Once artifacts and structures have been excavated or collected during surface surveys, they must be studied properly.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This process is known as post-excavation analysis, and is usually the most time-consuming part of an archaeological investigation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It is not uncommon for final excavation reports for major sites to take years to be published.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] At a basic level of analysis, artifacts found are cleaned, catalogued and compared to published collections.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This comparison process often involves classifying them typologically and identifying other sites with similar artifact assemblages.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] However, a much broader range of analytical techniques is available through archaeological science, allowing artifacts to be dated and their compositions examined.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Bones, plants, and pollen collected from a site can all be analysing using the methods of zooarchaeology, paleoethnobotany, palynology and stable isotopes while any texts can usually be deciphered.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] These techniques frequently provide information that would not otherwise be known, thereby contributing greatly to understanding a site.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] As with most academic disciplines, there are a very large number of archaeological sub-disciplines characterized by a specific method or type of material (e.g., lithic analysis, music, archaeobotany), geographical or chronological focus (e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Near Eastern archaeology, Islamic archaeology, Medieval archaeology), other thematic concern (e.g. maritime archaeology, landscape archaeology, battlefield archaeology), or a specific archaeological culture or civilization (e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Historical archaeology is the study of cultures with some form of writing and deals with objects and issues from the past.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In medieval Europe, archaeologists have explored the illicit burial of unbaptized children in medieval texts and cemeteries.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In downtown New York City, archaeologists have exhumed the 18th century remains of the African Burial Ground.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] When remnants of the WWII Siegfried Line were being destroyed, emergency archaeological digs were conducted whenever any part of the line was removed, to advance scientific knowledge and reveal details of its construction.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is the ethnographic study of living people, designed to aid in our interpretation of the archaeological record.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The approach first gained prominence during the processual movement of the 1960s, and continues to be a vibrant component of post-processual and other current archaeological approaches.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Early ethnoarchaeological research focused on hunter-gatherer or foraging societies; today, ethnoarchaeological research encompasses a much wider range of human behaviour.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Experimental archaeology represents the application of the experimental method to develop more highly controlled observations of processes that create and impact the archaeological record.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the context of the logical positivism of processualism with its goals of improving the scientific rigor of archaeological epistemologies, the experimental method gained importance.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Experimental techniques remain a crucial component to improving the inferential frameworks for interpreting the archaeological record.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry aims to systematize archaeological measurement.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It emphasizes the application of analytical techniques from physics, chemistry, and engineering.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It is a field of research that frequently focuses on determining the chemical composition of archaeological remains for source analysis.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry also investigates different spatial characteristics of features, employing methods such as space syntax techniques and geodesy as well as computer-based tools such as geographic information system technology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Rare earth elements patterns may also be used.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] A relatively nascent subfield is that of archaeological materials, designed to enhance understanding of prehistoric and non-industrial culture through scientific analysis of the structure and properties of materials associated with human activity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Digital Archeology is an interdisciplinary field that applies information technology (IT), digital tools, and data management techniques to archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] It includes virtual archeology and computational archeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Examples of digital archaeology include the use of computer graphics to create virtual 3D models of sites, like the throne room of an Assyrian palace or ancient Rome.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Photogrammetry and digital topographical models are combined with astronomical calculations to check if structures, such as pillars, align with astronomical events like the sun's position at a solstice.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Agent-based modelling and simulation are used to understand past social dynamics and outcomes.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Data mining is applied to large collections of archaeological 'grey literature'.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeology can be a subsidiary activity within Cultural resource management (CRM), also called Cultural heritage management (CHM) in the UK.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists frequently examine archaeological sites threatened by development.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] CRM accounts for most archaeological research done in the US and much of that in western Europe.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In the US, CRM archaeology has been a growing concern since the passage of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) of 1966.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Most scholars and politicians believe CRM has helped preserve much of the US's history and prehistory that would otherwise have been lost to the expansion of cities, dams, and highways.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Along with other statutes, the NHPA mandates that projects on federal land, or involving federal funds or permits, consider the effects of the project on each archaeological site.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The application of CRM in the UK is not limited to government-funded projects.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Since 1990, PPG 16 has required planners to consider archaeology as a material consideration in determining applications for new development.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] As a result, archaeological organizations undertake mitigation work in advance of or during construction in archaeologically sensitive areas, at the developer's expense.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Some of the largest archaeological projects ever undertaken in the UK are due to major infrastructure projects such as the A14 road improvement scheme and the construction of HS2.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In England, ultimate responsibility of care for the historic environment rests with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in association with English Heritage.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, the same responsibilities lie with Historic Scotland, Cadw and the Northern Ireland Environment Agency respectively.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] In France, the Institut national du patrimoine (The National Institute of Cultural Heritage) trains curators specialized in archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Their mission is to enhance the objects discovered.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The curator is the link between scientific knowledge, administrative regulations, heritage objects, and the public.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Among the goals of CRM are the identification, preservation, and maintenance of cultural sites on public and private lands, and the removal of culturally valuable materials from areas where they would otherwise be destroyed by human activity, such as proposed construction.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This study examines whether significant archaeological sites are present in the area affected by the proposed construction.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] If these do exist, time and money must be allotted for their excavation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] If initial survey and/or test excavations indicate the presence of an extraordinarily valuable site, the construction may be prohibited entirely.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Cultural resources management has been criticized.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] CRM is conducted by private companies that bid for projects by submitting proposals outlining the work to be done and the expected budget.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The agency responsible for the construction often chooses the proposal that asks for the least funding.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists face time pressure, often forced to complete their work in much less time than might be allotted to a purely academic project.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Compounding the time pressure is the vetting process for site reports that CRM firms are required to submit to the appropriate State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] From the SHPO's perspective, there is no difference between a report submitted by a CRM firm operating under a tight deadline and a multi-year academic project.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The ratio of open academic archaeology positions to the number of archaeology MA/MSc and PhD students is low.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] CRM, once an intellectual backwater for individuals with "strong backs and weak minds", has attracted these graduates, and CRM offices are increasingly staffed by advance degreed workers with a track record of producing scholarly articles, but who also have extensive CRM field experience.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The protection of archaeological finds for the public from catastrophes, wars, and armed conflicts is increasingly being implemented internationally.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This happens, on the one hand, through international agreements and, on the other hand, through organizations that monitor or enforce protection.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] United Nations, UNESCO, and Blue Shield International deal with the protection of cultural heritage, including archaeological sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This also applies to the integration of United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Blue Shield International has undertaken various fact-finding missions in recent years to protect archaeological sites during the wars in Libya, Syria, Egypt, and Lebanon.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The importance of archaeological finds for identity, tourism, and sustainable economic growth is repeatedly emphasized internationally.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The president of Blue Shield International, Karl von Habsburg, said during a cultural property protection mission in Lebanon in April 2019 with the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon: "Cultural assets are part of the identity of the people who live in a certain place.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] If you destroy their culture, you also destroy their identity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Early archaeology was largely an attempt to uncover spectacular artifacts and features or to explore vast, mysterious abandoned cities, and was mostly carried out by upper-class, scholarly men.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] This general tendency laid the foundation for the modern popular view of archaeology and archaeologists.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Many of the public view archaeology as something only available to a narrow demographic.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The job of archaeologist is depicted as a "romantic adventurist occupation", and as a hobby more than a job in the scientific community.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Cinema audiences form a notion of "who archaeologists are, why they do what they do, and how relationships to the past are constituted", and are often under the impression that all archaeology takes place in a distant and foreign land, only to collect monetarily or spiritually priceless artifacts.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] The modern depiction of archaeology has distorted the public's perception of what it is.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Much thorough and productive research has indeed been conducted in dramatic locales such as Copán and the Valley of the Kings, but the bulk of modern archaeological activity and finds is not so sensational.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeological adventure stories tend to ignore the painstaking work involved in carrying out modern surveys, excavations, and data processing.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Some archaeologists refer to such off-the-mark portrayals as "pseudoarchaeology".
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists are also highly reliant on public support; the question of for whom they work is often discussed.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Motivated by a desire to halt looting, curb pseudoarchaeology, and to help preserve archaeological sites through education and fostering public appreciation for the importance of archaeological heritage, archaeologists are mounting public-outreach campaigns.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] They seek to stop looting by combatting people who illegally take artifacts from protected sites, and by alerting people who live near archaeological sites of the threat of looting.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Common methods of public outreach include press releases, encouraging school field trips to sites under excavation led by professional archaeologists, and making reports and publications accessible outside academia.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Public appreciation of the significance of archaeology and archaeological sites often leads to improved protection from encroaching development or other threats.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] One audience for archaeologists' work is the public.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists increasingly realize that their work can benefit audiences outside the field and academia, and that they have a responsibility to educate and inform the public about archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Local heritage awareness is aimed at increasing civic and individual pride through projects such as community excavation programs and better public presentations of archaeological sites and knowledge.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Department of Agriculture, Forest Service (USFS) operates a volunteer archaeology and historic preservation program called the Passport in Time (PIT).
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Volunteers work with professional USFS archaeologists and historians on national forests throughout the U.S.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Volunteers are involved in all aspects of professional archaeology under expert supervision.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Television programs, web videos, and social media can also bring an understanding of underwater archaeology to a broad audience.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The *Mardi Gras* Shipwreck Project integrated a one-hour HD documentary, short videos for public viewing and video updates during the expedition as part of the educational outreach.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Webcasting is also another tool for educational outreach.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] For one week in 2000 and 2001, live underwater video of the *Queen Anne's Revenge* Shipwreck Project was webcast to the Internet as a part of the *QAR DiveLive* educational program that reached thousands of children around the world.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The American Academy of Underwater Sciences.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archived from the original on 19 February 2009.* Created and co-produced by Nautilus Productions and Marine Grafics, this project enabled students to talk to scientists and learn about methods and technologies used by the underwater archaeology team.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In the UK, popular archaeology programs such as *Time Team* and *Meet the Ancestors* have resulted in a huge upsurge in public interest.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Where possible, archaeologists now make more provisions for public involvement and outreach in larger projects than they once did, and many local archaeological organizations operate within the Community archaeology framework to expand public involvement in smaller-scale, more local projects.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeological excavation, however, is best undertaken by well-trained staff who can work quickly and accurately.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Often, this requires observing the necessary health and safety and indemnity insurance requirements when working on a modern building site with tight deadlines.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Certain charities and local government bodies sometimes offer places on research projects either as part of academic work or as a defined community project.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] There is also a flourishing industry selling places on commercial training excavations and archaeological holiday tours.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists prize local knowledge and often liaise with local historical and archaeological societies, which is one reason community archaeology projects are becoming more common.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Often, archaeologists are assisted by the public in the locating of archaeological sites, which professional archaeologists have neither the funding nor the time to do.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeological Legacy Institute (ALI), is a registered 501[c] [3] non-profit, media and education corporation registered in Oregon in 1999.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Pseudoarchaeology is an umbrella term for all activities that falsely claim to be archaeological but in fact violate commonly accepted and scientific archaeological practices.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] It includes much fictional archaeological work (discussed above), as well as some actual activity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Many non-fiction authors have ignored the scientific methods of processual archaeology, or the specific critiques of it contained in post-processualism.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] An example of this type is the writing of Erich von Däniken.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] His 1968 book, *Chariots of the Gods?*, together with many subsequent lesser-known works, expounds a theory of ancient contacts between human civilization on Earth and more technologically advanced extraterrestrial civilizations.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] This theory, known as palaeocontact theory, or Ancient astronaut theory, is not exclusively Däniken's, nor did the idea originate with him.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Works of this nature are usually marked by the renunciation of well-established theories based on limited evidence and the interpretation of evidence with a preconceived theory in mind.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Looting of archaeological sites is an ancient problem.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] For instance, many of the tombs of the Egyptian pharaohs were looted during antiquity.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeology stimulates interest in ancient objects, and people in search of artifacts or treasure cause damage to archaeological sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The commercial and academic demand for artifacts contributes directly to the illicit antiquities trade.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Smuggling antiquities abroad to private collectors has caused great cultural and economic damage in many countries whose governments lack the resources and/or the will to deter it.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Looters damage and destroy archaeological sites, denying future generations information about their ethnic and cultural heritage.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Indigenous peoples especially lose access to and control over their 'cultural resources', ultimately denying them the opportunity to know their past.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Hodge the director of the Southwest Museum released a statement that the museum would no longer purchase or accept collections from looted contexts.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The first conviction of the transport of artifacts illegally removed from private property under the Archaeological Resources Protection Act was in 1992 in the State of Indiana.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists trying to protect artifacts may be placed in danger by looters or locals trying to protect the artifacts from archaeologists, who are viewed as looters by the locals.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Some historical archaeological sites are looted by metal detector hobbyists who search for artifacts using increasingly advanced technology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Efforts are underway among all major Archaeological organizations to increase education and legitimate cooperation between amateurs and professionals in the metal detecting community.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] While most looting is deliberate, accidental looting can occur when amateurs, unaware of the importance of archaeological rigor, collect artifacts from sites and place them in private collections.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In the United States, examples such as the case of Kennewick Man have illustrated the tensions between Native Americans and archaeologists, which can be summarized as a conflict between a need to remain respectful toward sacred burial sites and the academic benefit from studying them.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] For years, American archaeologists dug on Indian burial grounds and other places considered sacred, removing artifacts and human remains to storage facilities for further study.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In some cases, human remains were not even thoroughly studied but instead archived rather than reburied.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Furthermore, Western archaeologists' views of the past often differ from those of tribal peoples.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The West views time as linear; for many natives, it is cyclic.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] From a Western perspective, the past is long-gone; from a native perspective, disturbing the past can have dire consequences in the present.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] As a consequence, American Indians attempted to prevent the archaeological excavation of sites inhabited by their ancestors.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] At the same time, American archaeologists believed that the advancement of scientific knowledge justified continuing their studies.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] This contradictory situation was addressed by the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA, 1990), which sought to reach a compromise by limiting research institutions' right to possess human remains.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In part due to the spirit of postprocessualism, some archaeologists have begun to actively enlist the assistance of indigenous peoples likely to be descended from those under study.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists have also been obliged to re-examine what constitutes an archaeological site in light of what native peoples consider sacred space.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] To many native peoples, natural features such as lakes, mountains, or even individual trees have cultural significance.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Australian archaeologists have particularly explored this issue and attempted to survey these sites to help protect them from development.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Such work requires close links and trust between archaeologists and the people they are trying to help and, at the same time, study.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] While this cooperation presents a new set of challenges and hurdles to fieldwork, it has benefits for all parties involved.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Tribal elders cooperating with archaeologists can prevent the excavation of areas of sites that they consider sacred, while the archaeologists gain the elders' aid in interpreting their finds.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] There have also been active efforts to recruit Aboriginal peoples directly into the archaeological profession.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] A new trend in the heated controversy between First Nations groups and scientists is the repatriation of native artifacts to the original descendants.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] An example of this occurred on 21 June 2005, when community members and elders from a number of the 10 Algonquian nations in the Ottawa area convened on the Kitigan Zibi reservation near Maniwaki, Quebec, to inter ancestral human remains and burial goods—some dating back 6,000 years.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] It was not determined, however, if the remains were directly related to the Algonquin people who now inhabit the region.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The remains may be of Iroquoian ancestry, since Iroquoian people inhabited the area before the Algonquin.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Moreover, the oldest of these remains might have no relation at all to the Algonquin or Iroquois and belong to an earlier culture that previously inhabited the area.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The remains and artifacts, including jewelry, tools and weapons, were originally excavated from various sites in the Ottawa Valley, including Morrison and the Allumette Islands.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] They had been part of the Canadian Museum of Civilization's research collection for decades, some since the late 19th century.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Elders from various Algonquin communities conferred on an appropriate reburial, eventually deciding on traditional red cedar and birch bark boxes lined with red cedar chips, muskrat and beaver pelts.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] An inconspicuous rock mound marks the reburial site, where nearly 80 boxes of various sizes are buried.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Because of this reburial, no further scientific study is possible.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Although negotiations between the Kitigan Zibi community and the museum were at times tense, they reached an agreement.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] African Diaspora Archaeology is an area of study within the subfield of historical archaeology that studies those that have been forcibly transported through the Atlantic Slave Trade, the Trans-Saharan Slave Trade, and the Indian Ocean Slave Trade, as well as their descendants.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Although of global relevance, most research has been conducted in the Americas and Africa.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In the 1990s, anthropologist Michael Blakey was the director of research during the New York African Burial Ground Project where he initiated a protocol for collaborating with the African descendant community.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In 2011, the Society of Black Archaeologists was created in the United States.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Co-founders Ayana Omilade Flewellen, archaeologist at the University of California, Riverside and Justin Dunnavant, archaeologist and assistant professor of anthropology at the University of California, Los Angeles intend to build a restorative justice-based structure in archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] They suggest defining descendants not only in genealogical terms, but also to welcome input of African Americans whose ancestors had a shared historical experience in enslavement.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The United States Senate unanimously passed a bill in December 2020 that centers African American cemeteries at risk in South Carolina.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The bill is made to protect historic African burial grounds and can lead to the creation of an African American Burial Grounds Network.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Barbados, eight days after becoming a republic on November 30, 2021, announced plans for the construction of the *Newton Enslaved Burial Ground Memorial* as well as a museum dedicated to the history of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The Ghanaian-British architect David Adjaye is to lead the project that is to commemorate an estimated 570 West Africans buried in unmarked graves at the site of the former Newton sugar plantation.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Barbados can be seen as a good example of respectful preservation of an African burial ground.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Throughout the Americas however the burial grounds are in danger of being destroyed or human remains are being excavated without the descendant community being involved.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] In 2022, residents on Sint Eustatius, Dutch Caribbean spoke out strongly against what they found were unethical excavations of their ancestors on the Godet African Burial Ground and the Golden Rock African Burial Ground.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] These climate drivers will result in changes to flora and fauna and to ground conditions (both on and below the surface), thereby affecting archaeological deposits and structures; human responses to the climate crisis will also impact archaeological sites.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The archaeologist's knowledge and skills are relevant to supporting society in adapting to a changing climate and a low-carbon future.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Another effect of higher temperatures has been the melting of glaciers and ice patches.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] This has led to the discovery of artifacts and bodies long buried in the ice, fostering the new field of glacial archaeology.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Archaeological sites can be seen as habitats that support ecosystems and fulfill biodiversity goals.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] As artificial intelligence (AI) continues to influence scientific research, its application in archaeological studies has become increasingly significant.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] For instance, AI models have been utilized to identify archaeological remains in the Empty Quarter of the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Additionally, AI technology has facilitated the discovery of 303 new geoglyphs in Nazca.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] AI is also useful in the translation of language and text, and can be used to help preserve cultural heritage.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Furthermore, with the help of LiDAR scanning, AI can also be used to create a 3D model of archaeological sites, such as in the Maya Lowlands where researchers are using these two technologies today.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] However, as the integration of AI in archaeology progresses, the risks in overuse of this become more apparent.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] The use of AI in archaeology creates a risk of oversimplification of data that is otherwise very complex.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] This oversimplification creates changes in how the data is interpreted, and creates concerns over the fostering of a deterministic view.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Another concern over AI is that it has the potential to perpetuate old and outdated ideas.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] As a tool AI will continue to grow in all scientific fields, with similar supportive and opposing arguments across all disciplines.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] While it can be used in some beneficial contexts, such as an instrument for translation, it also has the potential to do harm, such as the perpetuation of outdated ideas and the oversimplification of otherwise extremely complex data.
[src:gail-ashley/archaeology-p02] Kansa has called for archaeologists to resist replacing human-curated, open scholarship with commercial AI summaries that prioritize engagement and plausibility over truth and ethical stewardship .
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] The **Association for Women Geoscientists** (AWG) is an international professional organization which promotes the professional development of its members, provides geoscience outreach to girls, and encourages the participation of girls and women in the geosciences.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] Membership is open to all who support AWG's goals.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] Members include professional women and men from industry, government, museums and academia, students from a cross-section of colleges and universities, retirees, and others interested in supporting the society's goals.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] AWG was founded in San Francisco in 1977.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] The original purpose of the society was to provide encouragement to women in the geosciences, a career choice in which they were largely underrepresented at the time.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] As of 2006, the purpose remains the same despite the advances that have been made in the field, as AWG membership approaches 1200 students and scientists, reflecting the increasing participation of women in the geosciences.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] AWG is a 501(c)(6) mutual benefit corporation with local chapters in many cities and at-large members throughout the U.S. and around the world.
[src:gail-ashley/association-for-women-geoscientists] AWG is a member society of the American Geological Institute and the Geological Society of America.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The two most common bachelor's degrees are the Bachelor of Arts (BA) and the Bachelor of Science (BS or BSc).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] In countries with qualifications frameworks, bachelor's degrees are normally one of the major levels in the framework (sometimes two levels where non-honours and honours bachelor's degrees are considered separately).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] However, some qualifications titled bachelor's degree may be at other levels (e.g., MBBS) and some qualifications with non-bachelor's titles may be classified as bachelor's degrees (e.g. the Scottish MA and Canadian MD).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The term *bachelor* in the 12th century referred to a knight bachelor, who was too young or poor to gather vassals under his own banner.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] By the end of the 13th century, it was also used by junior members of guilds or universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] By folk etymology or wordplay, the word *baccalaureus* came to be associated with *bacca lauri* ("laurel berry"); this is in reference to laurels being awarded for academic success or honours.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] An honours degree generally requires a higher academic standard than a pass degree, and in some systems an additional year of study beyond the non-honours bachelor's.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] Some countries, such as Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Canada, have a postgraduate "bachelor with honours" degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] This may be taken as a consecutive academic degree, continuing on from the completion of a bachelor's degree program in the same field, or as part of an integrated honours program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] Programs like these typically require completion of a full year-long research thesis project.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] The map shows how long it takes for students in different countries to get a bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p01] It generally takes between 3 and 6 years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In most African countries, the university systems follow the model of their former colonizing power.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For example, the Nigerian university system is similar to the British system, while the Ivorian system is akin to the French.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The degree is typically identical to the program of France's universities, as specified in the LMD reform.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degree programs cover most of the fields in Algerian universities, except some fields, such as Medicine and Pharmaceutical Science.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees at the University of Botswana normally take four years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The system draws on both British and American models.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Degrees are classified as First Class, Second Class Division One (2:1), Second Class Division Two (2:2) and Third as in English degrees, but without being described as honours.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The main degrees are named by British tradition (Arts, Science, Law, etc.); in recent years, however, there have been a number of degrees named after specific subjects, such as Bachelor of Library and Information.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Kenya, university education is supported by the government.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree is awarded to students who successfully complete a three to seven-year course depending on the area of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For most degree programs, a research project and an internship period after which a report is written by the student is a must before the student is allowed to graduate.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In 2012, a number of select colleges were upgraded to university status in a bid to increase the intake of students into degree programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Morocco, a bachelor's degree is referred to as *al-ʾijāzah* (Arabic, French: **licence**).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The course of study takes three years, which are further divided into two cycles.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The first cycle comprises the first, or propaedeutic, year.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] After successfully completing their first two years, students can pursue either theoretical specialization (**études fondamentales**) or professional specialization (**études professionnelles**).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The second cycle is one year after whose completion students receive the **licence d'études fondamentales** or the *l*icence professionnelle**.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This academic degree system was introduced in September 2003.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] University admission is extremely competitive, with attendant advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Nonetheless, it takes four to five years to complete a bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In cases of poor performance, the time limit is double the standard amount of time.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For example, one may not study for more than 10 years for a five-year course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Students are normally asked to leave if they must take longer.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Nigerian universities offer BSc, BTech (usually from Universities of Technology), BArch (six years), and other specialized undergraduate degrees, such as BEng.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Science undergraduate degrees may require six months or a semester dedicated to SIWES (Students Industrial Work Experience Scheme) but it is usually mandatory for all engineering degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A semester for project work/thesis is required, not excluding course work, during the bachelor thesis in the final year.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The classifications of degrees: first-class, second-class (upper and lower), third-class (with honours; i.e., BSc (Hons)) and a pass (no honours).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] First- and second-class graduates are immediately eligible for advanced postgraduate degrees (i.e., MSc and PhD), but other classes may be required for an additional postgraduate diploma before such eligibility.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Furthermore, all graduating students are obliged to do the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC) requirement, which usually takes one year, after which they are eligible to pursue higher degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The NYSC is a paramilitary service that involves students' being posted to different parts of the country to serve in various capacities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Principal objectives of the NYSC are to forge national cohesion, encourage students to apply their obtained knowledge to solving problems of rural Nigeria, and others.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The NYSC was established by law after the Nigerian Civil War.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Polytechnical schools (polytechnics) in Nigeria are not considered universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] They are mandated to educate technicians of high calibre; they offer the OND (ordinary national diploma) and the HND (higher national diploma).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The polytechnics focus very strongly on practical technical training.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The BSc and HND are compared in engineering circles, but there are significant differences in training philosophies.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Honours degrees in Nigeria are differentiated only on the basis of performance.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Honours degrees include the first-class degree, second-class degrees (upper and lower) and the third-class degree, but not the pass.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All university students must do an independent research project which applies the knowledge obtained during the previous years of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The project work must be submitted in the semester before graduation and usually takes a significant number of points.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Further course work is not precluded during the project work, but the courses are fewer and are at an advanced level.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Project work is orally defended before the faculty and before peers.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the sciences and engineering a demonstration of the project is usually required.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In South Africa, an honours degree is an additional postgraduate qualification in the same area as the undergraduate major, and requires at least one further year of study as well as a research report.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most universities in Tunisia offer the 3-year bachelor's degree, except some fields, which are Medicine, Pharmacy, Engineering, Architecture and Bachelor of Science in Business Administration, solely offered by Tunis Business School and lasts 4 years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The region typically confers associates, bachelor's, master's, doctoral, and postdoctoral degrees to graduating students.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] University education in Argentina is currently regulated by the Ministry of Human Capital, with the requirements of a Licenciatura or bachelor's degree, also referred to as a university degree program lasting 4, 5, or more years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These programs can be equivalent to professional degrees, such as law, medicine, engineering, psychology, education, arts, architecture, industrial design, or bachelor's degrees more oriented towards research and teaching in a specific field of science.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The undergraduate degrees recognized by the Higher Education Law (LES) are programs that must have more than 2,600 hours of instruction, under the guidance of the National Commission for University Evaluation and Accreditation (CONEAU).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The current regulations govern the Institutional Distance Education System, Ministerial Resolution No.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 2641-E/2017 and Ministerial Resolution No.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There is no distinction between universities and non-university institutions, such as teacher training colleges.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Brazil, a bachelor's degree takes from three years to six years to complete depending on the course load and the program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree is the title sought by Brazilians in order to be a professional in a certain area of human knowledge.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Master's and doctoral degrees are additional degrees for those seeking an academic career or a specific understanding of a field.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Even without a formal adhesion to the Bologna system, a Brazilian "bachelor's" would correspond to a European "first cycle".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Depending on programs and personal choices, Europeans can achieve a master's degree in as little as four years (a three-year bachelor's and a one-year master's) and as long as six years (a four-year bachelor's, a two-year master's) of higher education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Education in Canada is governed independently by each province and territory; however, a common framework for degrees was agreed to by the Council of Ministers of Education, Canada, in 2007.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This adopted descriptors for bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees that were deliberately similar to those defined by the Bologna Process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This last category includes graduate-entry degrees titled as if they were doctorates, such as MD, JD and DDS degrees—despite their names, these are considered bachelor's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees may take either three or four years to complete and are awarded by colleges and universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In many universities and colleges, bachelor's degrees are differentiated either as (ordinary) bachelor's or as honours bachelor's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The term "honours" is an academic distinction, which indicates that students must achieve their bachelor's degree with a sufficiently high overall grade point average; in addition, some programs may require more education than non-honours programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The honours degrees are sometimes designated with the abbreviation in brackets of "(Hon(s))".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Going back in history, the *Bachelor with Honours* (Latin *baccalaureatus cum honore*, French: *baccalauréat spécialisé*) was traditionally taken as the highest undergraduate degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The program requires at least 4 years of studies, with strong emphasis on the research-based *Honours Seminar Thesis* which is considered approximately equivalent to a formal master's thesis.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Universities show the academic degree as well as the possible honours distinction (Latin honours) on the diploma (e.g., "*BACCALAUREATUS ARTIUM CUM HONORE ...
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Quebec, students have to take a minimum of two years of college before entering, for example, a three-year Bachelor of Science (BSc) or a four-year Bachelor of Engineering (BEng) program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the province of Ontario, the most bachelor's degrees offered by Ontario universities are academic in nature.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In contrast, Ontario legislation requires bachelor's degrees offered by Ontario colleges to be applied and vocationally focused.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Currently, the trend is for universities not to offer a bachelor's degree and to offer instead a licentiate's or "*ingeniero*" degree after five years of education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees may take an average of five years (from four to five years) to complete depending on the course load and the program, they are awarded by colleges and universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Each college has its own curriculum and requirements with an emphasis of their choice, governed independently by each state of the republic.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] After finishing all the subjects the student require a final work, which means the completion of particular honours seminars, research and development or a written thesis in a particular field.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This requirement takes about six months to one year depending on the type of degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degree should not be falsely related with its Spanish cognate "bachiller", which designate a prerequisite for matriculate in a career or bachelor studies.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The official name for a bachelor's degree in Mexico is "licenciado" and such studies are referred as "licenciatura".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees should not be confused with Engineering Degrees, where an *Ingeniería* is prefixed to the name and requires additional courses for certification as an Engineer.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Those students are awarded the same bachelor's degree as students completing the standard curriculum but with the notation *in cursu honorum* on the transcript and the diploma.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Usually, the above Latin honours are separate from the notation for this honours course, but a student in the honours course generally must maintain grades worthy of at least the *cum laude* notation anyway.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Hence, a graduate might receive a diploma *Artium Baccalaureatum rite* or *Artium Baccalaureatum summa cum laude* in the regular course or *Artium Baccalaureatum summa cum laude in cursu honorum* in the honours course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] If the student has completed the requirements for an honours degree only in a particular discipline (e.g., English language and literature), the degree is designated accordingly (e.g., "BA with Honours in English").
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In this case, the degree candidate will complete the normal curriculum for all subjects except the selected discipline ("English", in the preceding example).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The requirements in either case usually require completion of particular honours seminars, independent research at a level higher than usually required (often with greater personal supervision by faculty than usual), and a written honours thesis in the major subject.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Requirements for such notations of honours generally include minimum grade point averages (GPA), with the highest average required for the *summa* distinction (or *maxima*, when that distinction is present).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Six notable exceptions are Reed College, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, The Evergreen State College, Sarah Lawrence College, Bard College, and Bennington College, which do not have deans' lists, Latin honours recognitions, or undergraduate honours programs or subjects.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Starting in 2023, some colleges and universities began offering three-year bachelor's programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] As of late 2025, 70 institutions had the programs or planned to.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A three-year degree could be obtained with additional credits during the regular school year and summer courses.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most reduced the number of required credits, identifying the program as "accelerated pathways" on the transcript.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Reasons for choosing a three-year program include the increasing cost of education, and the desire of students not to take courses they did not need.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Engineering universities provide four-year degree programs for bachelor's degree courses of study (BSc in Eng and BSc).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Medical colleges have five-year degree programmes (MBBS, BDS).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In law education there is a two-year LLB degree after completing three years in a BA program for a total of five years of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There is also a four-year LLB honours degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The Bachelor of Architecture (BArch) and Bachelor of Pharmacy (BPharm) are professional degrees awarded to students who complete a five-year course of study in the field at some universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All of these programs begin after achieving the Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC – in total 12 years of school education).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] There are 13 kinds of *statutory* bachelor's degrees in China: Bachelor of Philosophy, Economics, Laws, Education, Arts, History, Science, Engineering, Agriculture, Medicine, Management, Military Science, and Fine Arts.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Since the undergraduate education system in China is modeled after its American counterpart, all of the degrees are adapted from those of the United States except for the issuing of the degree certificate.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Once a student has fulfilled their course requirements, a "graduate certificate" will be given.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In order to get the degree, a student must finish and pass the dissertation stage; only then will they be awarded a degree certified by the Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most bachelor's degree in China needs four years to complete, with the exception that the Bachelor of Medicine degree requires five years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Any Chinese citizen can also get a bachelor's degree via the undergraduate majors of the Self-Taught Higher Education Examinations (Chinese: 高等教育自学考试).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In Indonesia, most of the current bachelor's degrees are domain-specific degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Therefore, there are more than 20 bachelor's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The historical situation in Austria was very similar to that in Germany, with the traditional first degrees being the *magister* and the *diplom*, which are master's-level qualifications.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] From 2004, bachelor's degrees have been reintroduced as part of the Bologna Process reforms.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These can be studied at universities, leading to a bachelor's degree (BA or BSc) after three or four years, and at Fachhochschulen (universities of applied science), leading to a *bachelor (FH)* after three years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Education in Belgium is run by the language communities, with separate higher education systems being administered by the Flemish Community and the French Community.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Both systems have been reformed to align with the Bologna Process, the Flemish Community from 2003 and the French Community from 2004.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the Flemish Community, bachelor's degrees may be either academic or professional.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] These degrees last three years, and may be followed in both cases by an advanced bachelor diploma (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor'), lasting one year (cf. the Australian bachelor honours degree).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All of these qualifications are at level 6 on the EQF, to which the Flemish Qualification Framework was referenced in June 2011.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the French Community, universities award *grade de bachelier* (3 years) as the equivalent of bachelor's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Outside of universities, professional programs may be *type long* (long type) or *type court* (short type), both of which are offered at *hautes ecoles* and *ecoles supérieures des arts*.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The long type takes in a *grade de bachelier (type long)* (3 years), which is followed by a *master* degree (1 or 2 years), while the short type has a *grade de bachelier professionnalisant (type court)* (3 years), which may be followed by a *bachelier de spécialisation* (1 year).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All *bachelier* degrees (including the *bachelier de spécialisation*) are equivalent to level 6 of the EQF, but have not been formally referenced.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Most public universities and community colleges in Croatia today offer a three-year bachelor program, which can be followed up typically with a two-year master's (graduate) program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] All bachelor's degrees in Croatia are professional.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] For distinction, in universities the title is "univ. bacc." (university bachelor) and in community colleges is just "bacc.".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Zagreb School of Economics and Management has a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Academies that specialize in the arts, e.g. the Academy of Fine Arts in Zagreb, have four-year bachelor's programs followed by a one-year master's.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Higher education in Cyprus is aligned with the Bologna Process and governed by the *Cyprus Agency of Quality Assurance and Accreditation in Higher Education* (CYQAA).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees at Cypriot universities are four years in duration, corresponding to 240 ECTS credits.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Public universities in Cyprus comprise the University of Cyprus, the Cyprus University of Technology and the Open University of Cyprus, all of which admit students through the annual Pancyprian Examinations.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Private universities, including the European University Cyprus and the University of Nicosia, admit students on the basis of academic records and offer programs in Greek and English.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Historically, the baccalaureus was the undergraduate degree awarded to students who graduated from the course of trivium (grammar, dialectic and rhetoric) at a faculty of liberal arts (either at the Charles University or at the University of Olomouc).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] It was a necessary prerequisite to continue either with the faculty of liberal arts (quadrivium leading to a master's degree and further to a doctoral degree) or to study at one of the other three historical faculties—law, medicine or theology.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] A bachelor's degree, abbreviated BcA, in the field of fine arts, and Bc (*Bakalář* in Czech) in other fields is awarded for accredited undergraduate programs at universities and colleges.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The vast majority of undergraduate programmes offered in the Czech Republic have a standard duration of three years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] In the Czech tertiary education system, most universities and colleges today offer a three-year bachelor program, which can be followed up typically with a two-year master's (graduate) program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] Some specializations, such as doctors of medicine and veterinary doctors, hold exceptions from the general system in that the only option is a six-year master's program with no bachelor stage (graduate with title doctor).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] This is due mainly to the difficulty of meaningfully splitting up the education for these specialisations.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The bachelor's degree was re-introduced at universities in Denmark in 1993, after the original degree (baccalaureus) was abandoned in 1775.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p02] The bachelor's degree is awarded after three or four years of study at a university and follows a scheme quite similar to the British one.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, both in the business and the academic world in Denmark, the bachelor's degree is still considered to be "the first half" of a master's (candidatus).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is often not considered a degree in its own right, despite the politicians' best attempts to make it more accepted.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree has also been used since the late 1990s in a number of areas like nursing and teaching.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Usually referred to as a "professional bachelor" (Danish: *professionsbachelor*), these degrees usually require 3 to 4+1⁄2 years of combined theoretical and practical study at a "professional university college" (Danish: *professionshøjskole*) or "business academy" (Danish: "erhvervsakademier").
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These professional bachelor's degrees do grant access to some university master's program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These professional bachelor's degrees are considered to be a full education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional bachelor's degree is the equivalent of the French *Licence* three-year degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Since the new European system of 2004 LMD Bologna process was founded, it has become standard to recognize a bachelor's degree over three years with a *licence* degree, a master's degree over five years, and a doctorate over eight years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some private institutions are however literally naming their degrees *bachelor.* Some of these *bachelor* are "*Diplômes visés*" (often delivered by specialized private schools, such as business, design, film or journalism schools), others are "*Diplômes certifiés*" by the French State.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The others are not accredited by the French State.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Historically, the bachelor's degree, called "*Bakkalaureus*", existed in Germany since the late Middle Ages.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] But it was abolished by the educational reforms undertaken in 1820.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Abitur degree – the final degree received in school after a specialized 'college phase' of two years – replaced it, and universities only awarded graduate degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The magister degree, a graduate degree, was awarded after five years of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 1899, a second graduate degree, the diplom, was introduced when the *Technische Hochschulen* (TH) received university status.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] With the introduction of the universities of applied sciences, a shortened version of the latter, referred to as *Diplom (FH)* and designed to take three to four years, was phased in between 1969 and 1972.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, in 1998, in order to comply with the European *Bologna process*, a new educational law reintroduced the bachelor's degree (first degree after three years of study) in Germany.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Today, these degrees can be called either "*Bakkalaureus*" or "bachelor" (in accordance with federal law), but the English term is more common.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] According to the Bologna model, the bachelor is followed by the post-graduate master's degree of another two years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional degrees of diplom and magister were mostly abolished in 2010, although the diplom still persists in a few subjects and universities and has been reintroduced as alternative degree in some places.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The traditional degrees have been re-mapped to the new European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) point system to make them comparable to the new bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Greek bachelor's degree is called πτυχίο (transliterated to "ptychio"; Greek: πτυχίο; ptychio in dhimotiki from 1976–present; or defunct πτυχίον; ptychion in polytonic, katharevousa up until 1976).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is earned after four to six years of undergraduate studies, depending on the field, and is a first cycle qualification in the Bologna Process with 240 or more ECTS credits.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is placed at level 6 of the national qualifications framework of Greece which is officially named Hellenic Qualification Framework (HQF), which is referenced to level 6 of the European Qualifications Framework.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is classified as a level 6 qualification in the ISCED.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree is provided by all Higher Education Institutions (HEIs), including universities, specialist HEIs, formerly technological educational institutes (TEIs) (1983–2019).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 1995, it changed TEI six-semester-mode of undergraduate degree programme of studies legally equivalent to an ordinary bachelor's degree (Ord) (3+1⁄2-year; 210 ECTS, 1983–1995) into nine-semester-mode (4-year; 240 ECTS, 1995–2019).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Technical universities and some universities offer a five-year (300 ECTS) undergraduate programme leading to a Δίπλωμα (Greek) Diploma (integrated-master-level-granting, Master's degree equivalent) at Level 7 of the HQF.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the classic, pre-Bologna educational system, Hungarian academic programs were not divided into bachelor's and master's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, while an average university (Hungarian: *egyetem*) degree lasted 5 years, there were undergraduate college (Hungarian: *főiskola*) degrees obtainable, in either 3 or 4 years of length.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These diplomas are today considered to be equivalents of a BA/BSc (undergraduate college) or an MA/MSc (university) degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Bologna System was introduced in 2005, and with the last classes graduating in 2009, it is the sole form of higher education in the country.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees (Hungarian: *alapképzés*, "basic degree") usually last 3 years, but there are degrees in certain areas of education – most notably engineering, economics, and some natural sciences – where an additional semester is required, lengthening the program to 3,5 years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In order to graduate, students must earn credits (ECTS) and write a thesis for which students have to elaborate on an argument under the supervision of a professor (generally from three to eight ECTS).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] According to each faculty internal ruling, a *lode* may be awarded to candidates with a 110/110 mark for recognition of the excellence of the final project.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the bachelor's degree was introduced in 2002 with the change of the Dutch degree system due to the European Bologna process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Until that time, the Dutch universities did not have a Bachelor level degree (although the Candidate's diploma existed until 1982, which was more-or-less of the same level).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Prior to the Dutch degree system change a single program at the university comprised the same course load as the bachelor's and master's programs together which led to the doctorandus degree (or for legal studies to the "Meester in de rechten" and engineering to "Ingenieur").
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 2002, with the introduction of the Bachelor's master's doctorate system, the single (4- or 5-year) program at Dutch universities has been changed and split into a 3-year program leading to the bachelor's degree and a subsequent a 1- or 2-year program leading to the master's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Those who had already started the doctorandus program could, upon completing it, opt for the doctorandus degree (before their name, abbreviated to 'drs.'), or simply use the master's degree (behind their name) in accordance with the new standard.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Since these graduates do not have a separate bachelor's degree (which is in fact – in retrospect – incorporated into the program), the master's degree is their first academic degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In 2003/2004, the Dutch degree system was changed because of the Bologna process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] While the titles ing., bc., ir., mr., drs. and dr. are used before one's own name, the degrees B, M or D are mentioned after one's name.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is still allowed to use the traditional titles.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Whether a bachelor's degree is granted by a *hogeschool* or university is highly relevant since these parallel systems of higher education have traditionally served somewhat different purposes, with the vocational colleges mainly concentrating on skills and practical training.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A BA or BSc from a university grants "immediate" entry into a master's program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Moreover, this is usually considered a formality to allow students to switch to foreign universities master's programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Recently, HBO (vocational) master's degrees have been introduced in the Netherlands.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Graduates thereof may use neither the extension "of Arts" (MA) nor "of Science" (MSc).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] They may use an M followed by the field of specialization (e.g., MDes).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] This year of study to "convert" from the vocational to academic (WO – *wetenschappelijk onderwijs*, literally "scientific education") is also known as a "bridge" or "premasters" year.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Despite the use of the terminology "university of applied science" the higher vocational colleges are not considered to be "universities" within the Netherlands.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In February 2011, the Dutch State Secretary of Education decided to adhere to the recommendations written in a report by the Veerman Commission.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the near future, the distinction between academic and higher vocational degrees will disappear.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In Spain, due to the ongoing transition to a model compliant with the Bologna agreement, exact equivalents to the typical Anglosphere bachelor's degree and master's degree are being implemented progressively.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The "título de grado" is now the prerequisite to access a master's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The "título de máster" is now the prerequisite to access doctoral studies, and its duration and the kind of institutions that can teach these programs are regulated in the framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Up until 2009/2010, the system was split into three categories of degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The official first-cycle degrees are comparable in terms of duration, scope, and educational outcomes to an Anglo-Saxon bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Meanwhile, the second-cycle degrees are comparable in terms of duration, scope, and educational outcomes to an Anglo-Saxon bachelor's + master's degrees combination if compared with the Anglo-Saxon system.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor's degree is the standard undergraduate degree in the United Kingdom, with the most common degrees being the Bachelor of Arts (BA) and Bachelor of Science (BSc).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Most bachelor's degree courses (apart from the very rare postgraduate awards, and those in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science) lead to honours degrees, with ordinary degrees generally only being awarded to those who do not meet the required pass mark for an honours degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] With the exception of the postgraduate bachelor's degrees and bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science, UK bachelor's degrees (whether honours or non-honours) are first cycle (end of cycle) qualifications under the Bologna Process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Postgraduate bachelor's degrees and bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are second cycle (end of cycle) qualifications.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science offer intercalated degrees en route to the final qualification.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees should not be confused with baccalaureate qualifications, which derive their name from the same root.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In the UK, baccalaureate qualifications, e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] International Baccalaureate, Welsh Baccalaureate, English Baccalaureate, are gained at secondary schools rather than being degree-level qualifications.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Until the 19th century, a bachelor's degree represented the first degree in a particular faculty, with Arts representing undergraduate study, thus the Bachelor of Civil Law (BCL) at Oxford and the Bachelor of Laws (LLB) at Cambridge, for example, were postgraduate degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The same historical usage of indicating an undergraduate degree by it being in the faculty of arts rather than being a bachelor's degree gives rise to the Oxbridge MA and the Scottish MA).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In England, Wales and Northern Ireland, bachelor's degrees usually take three years of study to complete, although courses may take four years where they include a year abroad or a placement year.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Degrees may have titles related to their broad subject area or faculty, such as BA or BSc, or may be more subject specific (e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The majority of bachelor's degrees are now honours degrees, although this has not always been the case historically.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Although first degree courses are usually three years (360 credits), direct second year entry is sometimes possible for students transferring from other courses or those who have completed foundation degrees, via accreditation of prior learning or more formal credit transfer arrangements.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some universities compress the three-year course into two years by teaching for a full calendar year (180 credits) rather than a standard academic year (120 credits), thus maintaining the full 360-credit extent of the course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In addition to bachelor's degrees, some institutions offer integrated master's degrees as first degrees in some subjects (particularly in STEM fields).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These integrate teaching at bachelor's and master's level in a four-year (five-year if with industrial experience) course, which often shares the first two years with the equivalent bachelor's course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The normal academic standard for bachelor's degrees in England, Wales and Northern Ireland is the *honours degree*.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some institutions have announced that they intend to replace this system of classifying honours degrees with an American-style Grade Point Average.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An *ordinary* (or *unclassified*) degree, which only requires passes worth 300 credits rather than the 360 of the honours degree, may be awarded if a student has completed the full honours degree course but has not obtained sufficient passes to earn a degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Completion of just the first two years of the course can lead to a Diploma of Higher Education and completion of only the first year to a Certificate of Higher Education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] On the Framework for Higher Education Qualifications, standard undergraduate bachelor's degrees with and without honours are at level 6, although the courses include learning across levels 4 to 6.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees normally require 360 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 6, while ordinary degrees need 300 credits with a minimum of 60 at level 6.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are at level 7, with learning spanning levels 4 to 7, and are not normally credit rated.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The Diploma of Higher Education is a level 5 (second year of bachelor's degree) qualification and requires 240 credits, a minimum of 90 at level 5; The Certificate of Higher Education is a level 4 (first year of bachelor's degree) qualification and requires 120 credits, a minimum of 90 at level 4.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees may be awarded as BA (Hons) or MA (Hons) in the arts and social sciences, or BSc (Hons) for sciences, or have more specific titles such as BEng.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As in the rest of the UK, integrated master's degrees, taking five years in Scotland, are also offered as first degrees alongside bachelor's degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An honours degree may be directly linked to professional or vocational qualifications, particularly in fields such as engineering, surveying and architecture.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These courses tend to have highly specified curricula, leaving students without many options for broader study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Others, following a more traditional route, start off with a broad range of studies across the faculty that has admitted the student or, via modular study, across the whole university.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Students on these courses specialise later in their degree programmes.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Typically degree grades are based only on the final two years of study, after a specialisation has been chosen, so broader study courses taken in the first two years do not affect the final degree grade.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours degrees are subdivided into classes in the same way as the rest of the UK, depending on the overall grade achieved.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These are, from highest to lowest; first class, upper second class (2:1), lower second class (2:2), and third class.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Ordinary degrees are awarded to students who have completed three years at university studying a variety of related subjects.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] These may be taken over a broad range of subjects or (as with honours degrees) with a specialisation in a particular subject (in the latter case, they are sometimes known as *designated degrees*).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As ordinary degrees in Scotland constitute a distinct course of study, rather than a grade below honours degrees, they can be graded (from lowest to highest) as "pass", "merit" or "distinction".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] As in the rest of the UK, Certificates and Diplomas of Higher Education may be earned by those completing one and two years of a bachelor's degree course respectively.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The first two years, sometimes three, of both an ordinary degree and an honours degree are identical, but candidates for the ordinary degree study in less depth in their final year and often over a wider variety of subjects, and do not usually complete a dissertation.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A Scottish ordinary degree is thus different from ordinary degrees in the rest of the UK in comprising a distinct course of study from the honours degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In keeping with the Scottish "broad education" philosophy, ordinary degrees (and more rarely honours ones) may mix different disciplines such as sciences and humanities taught in different faculties and in some cases even different universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees with honours are at level 10 of the Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework (SCQF) and require 480 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 10 and 90 at level 9.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Ordinary degrees are at level 9 and require 360 credits with a minimum of 90 at level 9.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Both honours degrees and ordinary degrees qualify as first cycle (end of cycle) qualifications in the Bologna Process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor's degrees in medicine, dentistry and veterinary science are at level 11 of the SCQF and are second cycle (end of cycle) qualifications in the Bologna Process.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In Australia, a "bachelor degree" is normally a three to four-year program, leading to a qualification at level 7 of the Australian Qualifications Framework.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Entry to a number of professions, such as law practice and teaching, require a bachelor's degree (a 'professional' degree).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Other degrees, such as Bachelor of Arts do not necessarily elicit entry into a profession, though many organisations require a bachelor's degree for employment.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A one-year postgraduate bachelor honours degree can be achieved as a consecutive stand-alone course following a bachelor's degree in the same field, or as an additional year as part of a bachelor's degree program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The honours course is normally only open to those who do well in their bachelor's degree program and involves study at a more advanced level than that bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Both the bachelor and bachelor honours degrees are aligned with level 6 of the EQF, the same as British and Irish bachelor's degrees with and without honours, and other Bologna Process first cycle qualifications.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some bachelor's degrees (e.g. engineering and environmental science) include an integrated honours degree as part of a four-year program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Honours is generally for students who want to take up a research track for postgraduate studies, and increasingly for those who want an extra edge in the job market.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Bachelor honours degrees include a major Independent research component, allowing students to develop skills that will enable them to proceed to further study or to work in research roles in industry.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] First-class or second-class (upper division) honours are generally required for entry into doctoral programs (e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] PhDs, etc.); an alternative route to doctoral study is via a "masters degree".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The colonial link and the establishment of the University of the South Pacific in 1968 allowed the education system to follow suit from the qualification system of the Commonwealth.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] University of the South Pacific is the only university in the Oceania region to be internationally recognized outside Australia and New Zealand with its bachelor's and other awards program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] It is also the highest ranked in the university ranking in the island region and also ranked above some Australian universities like the University of Canberra, University of Sunshine Coast and New Zealand universities like Lincoln University and Waikato Institute of Technology.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] In New Zealand, only recognised institutions – usually universities and polytechnics – have degree-awarding powers.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Most bachelor's degrees are three years full-time, but certain degrees, such as the Bachelor of Laws and the Bachelor of Engineering degrees, require four years of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A bachelor with honours is a program of four years duration (e.g., Bachelor of Arts with Honours).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A Bachelor of Medicine degree requires a minimum of six years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Where students opt to study two bachelor's degrees simultaneously – referred to as a "conjoint degree" or "double degree" – an extra year of study is added.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The number of years of study required is determined based on the degree with the greatest number of years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] For example, a BCom degree requires three years of full-time study, but a double BCom–LLB degree will require five years of full-time study because the LLB degree is four years long.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Exceptional students may choose to complete a degree in a shorter amount of time by taking on extra courses, usually with the help of summer school.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Students who complete a double degree program will have two separate bachelor's degrees at the end of their studies.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Consistently high-performing students may also be invited to complete the 'honours' program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] The bachelor with honours usually requires an extra year of study with an extra honours thesis/dissertation.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] This degree is considered to fall between the bachelor's and master's levels on the European Qualifications Framework.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] An honours award is indicated by the addition of "Hons" to the degree name or abbreviation (for example, "Bachelor of Laws (Hons)").
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] Some honours degree courses also offer a postgraduate diploma (PGDip) as an exit qualification, which often consists of the same workload but with added flexibility.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A PGDip does not usually require a dissertation.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] However, the student may complete one if desired.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p03] A diploma award is indicated by "PGDip" and the degree field (for example, "PGDipArts" or "PGDipScience".
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Many other specialized bachelor's degrees are offered as well.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some are in very specialized areas, like the five-year BIDes or BScIDes degree in industrial design.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Others are offered only at a limited number of universities, such as the Walsh School of Foreign Service at Georgetown University's Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service (BSFS).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The University of Delaware offers a Bachelor of Applied Arts and Science (BAASc) degree, a degree which often indicates an interdisciplinary course of study for many majors within its School of Arts and Science.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Stanford University's Bachelor of Arts and Science degree is for students who are receiving one degree but who have completed two arts and sciences majors, one of which would ordinarily lead to the BA and one of which would ordinarily lead to the BSc.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Rules on this vary considerably, however.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Agriculture (BAgr) offers a broad training in the sciences.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The focus of this four-year applied degree is on the development of analytical, quantitative, computing and communication skills.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Students learn how to apply the knowledge and principles of science to the understanding and management of the production, processing and marketing of agricultural products, and to the management and conservation of our natural resources.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] This can include ecological agriculture.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Architecture (BArch) degree is a professional degree awarded to students who complete the five-year course of study in the field at some universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Many universities offer a BSc or BA (majoring in architecture) after the first three or four years, and then a post-graduate diploma, BArch or MArch for the following two to four years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Design (BDes) is awarded to those who complete the four- or four-and-a-half-year course of study in design, usually majoring in a specific field of design, such as interior design or graphic design.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Industrial Design (BID) is an undergraduate academic degree awarded by a university for a four-year course of study that specializes on the design of industrial products.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some colleges also offer four-year B.I.D. programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Arts degrees (BA, AB; also known as *Artium Baccalaureus*) along with the Bachelor of Science degrees are the most common undergraduate degrees given.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Originally, in the universities of Oxford, Cambridge and Dublin, all undergraduate degrees were in the faculty of arts, hence the name of the degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Applied Arts and Sciences (BAASc) is an undergraduate degree that bridges academic and work-life experiences.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] There are various undergraduate degrees in information technology incorporating programming, database design, software engineering, networks and information systems.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] These programs prepare graduates for further postgraduate research degrees or for employment in a variety of roles in the information technology industry.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The program focus may be on the technical or theoretical aspects of the subject matter, depending on which course is taken.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A Bachelor of Economics (BEcon, BSc(Econ) and BEc) is awarded in British and Commonwealth institutions after following a rigorous programme of theoretical quantitative economic learning.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programmes usually include study of both microeconomics and macroeconomics, alongside empirical work in the form of econometrics.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Economics can also be offered as a Bachelor of Science (with a more general focus on the quantitative methods) or a Bachelor of Arts (with a qualitative focus on the concepts).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Economics is substantially more theoretical and mathematical than the more commonly offered brethren.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In countries following British tradition (the University of Malta is an exception), medical students pursue an undergraduate medical education and receive bachelor's degrees in medicine and surgery (MBBChir, MBBS, BMBS, BM, MBChB, etc.).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although notionally MB and BS are two degrees, they must be taken together.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In some Irish universities, a third degree, Bachelor of Arts in Obstetrics (BAO), is added.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, this third degree is an anachronism from the 19th century and is not registerable with the Irish Medical Council.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the UK, these qualifications, while retaining the title of bachelor's degrees, are master's degree level qualifications.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Use of the courtesy title of *doctor* is attached to the profession of doctor or physician and is granted by registration, not by earning the qualifying degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Trainee doctors in the UK are allowed to use the title once they begin their training and receive provisional registration.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Canadian MD degree is, despite its name, classified as a bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Dentistry is offered both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In countries following the British model, the first degree in dentistry is the Bachelor of Dental Surgery, which is a master's degree level qualification in the UK.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In some parts of the world, the doctorate of dental surgery (DDS) is the usual undergraduate program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Postgraduate courses such as the Bachelor of Dentistry (BDent) – awarded exclusively by the University of Sydney in Australia – require a previous bachelor's degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Midwifery degree is a professional degree awarded to students who have complete a three- to five-year (depending on the country) course of study in midwifery.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Common abbreviations include BScMid, BM, BMid and BHScMid.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Physiotherapy is offered both as an undergraduate and a graduate course of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Studies leading to the Bachelor of Physiotherapy (BPT) degree usually constitute the undergraduate program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the graduate program, courses leading to a degree such as the Master of Physiotherapy degree are offered.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the Canadian province of Quebec, French universities offer both undergraduate and graduate courses leading to the procurement of a Bachelor of Science degree with a major in physiotherapy and a Master of Science degree specialized in physiotherapy.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] McGill University, the Université de Montréal, and the Université de Sherbrooke are among the post-secondary institutions that offer such programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Optometry is a four-year or five-year course.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although students graduate with a BSc after three years of study, passing a further supervised preregistration year is required to become a fully qualified optometrist.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The National Institute of Ophthalmic Sciences is among the post-secondary institutions that offer such programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is the academic arm of The Tun Hussein Onn National Eye Hospital and the only eye hospital based institution in Malaysia.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Nursing degree is a three- to five-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for a career in nursing.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Often the degree is required to gain "registered nurse", or equivalent, status—subject to completion of exams in the area of residence.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Sometimes, though, the degree is offered only to nurses who are already registered.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Alternative titles include Bachelor of Science in Nursing and Bachelor of Nursing Science, with abbreviations BScN, BN and BNSc.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Paramedicine is offered both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate course in some countries.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Paramedicine (BScP, BP, BHScP) is a three- to a five-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for a career in paramedicine, paramedic services or emergency medical services.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Countries such as Canada, United Kingdom, Ireland, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa have established paramedicine degree programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The United States does not require a degree for paramedicine practice.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Veterinary Science program is generally a five-year course of study that is required for becoming a veterinarian.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is also known as the Bachelor of Veterinary Medicine and Surgery at some universities (BVMS).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the UK, this is a master's degree level qualification that retains the title of bachelor's for historical reasons.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, no bachelor's degree of veterinary science is given, only the Doctor of Veterinary Medicine (DVM) degree is.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Pharmacy (BPharm) degree is a common undergraduate degree for the practice of pharmacy.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, Canada, and France, however, all colleges of pharmacy have now phased out the degree in favor of the PharmD, or doctor of pharmacy, degree or the PhD, doctor of philosophy, degree in pharmacy.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some universities, such as the University of Mississippi, award a Bachelor of Science in Pharmaceutical Sciences (BScPSc) degree as a part of the seven-year PharmD program after the completion of the first four years.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, the BScPSc degree does not qualify the recipient for the practice of pharmacy, for which students must earn a PharmD degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Public health is usually studied at the master's degree level.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Australia is one of the few countries where studies in Public Health are available at undergraduate level.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Indeed, Australian undergraduate students may major in specific areas of Public Health such as Health Promotion/Education, Epidemiology, Healthcare Administration and Public Health Nutrition.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in Public Health (BScPH) degree is a four-year undergraduate degree that prepares students for careers in the public, private, or nonprofit sectors in areas such as public health, environmental health, health administration, epidemiology, or health policy and planning.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Kinesiology degree (BK or BScK)is a specialized degree in the field of human movement and kinetics.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some schools still offer the subject under the aegis of a School of Physical Education as a Bachelor of Physical Education (BPE or BPhEd), although "kinesiology" or "human kinetics" is currently the more popularly accepted term for the discipline.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The degree is awarded following four to six years of collegiate study in America (average five years), from three to four in Europe and Australia.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In America (especially Latin America), Nutrition per se is separated from Dietetics, where the latter is equivalent to a technical degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Aviation (BAv) is awarded to students who complete a four-year course of study in the field of aviation.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Traditionally, the BD was a graduate degree rather than a first degree and typically emphasised academic theology, biblical languages, etc.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] However, this has become a less common arrangement.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] While the theological bachelor's degree is generally conferred upon completion of a four-year program, it is also conferred in some specialized three-year programs.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] From there, the next level of advancement is generally the Master of Divinity (MDiv), Master of Theology (ThM), Master of Religious Studies, or Master of Religious Education (MRE) degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, the "mainline" Protestant clergy typically take a four-year bachelor's degree in whatever field they choose, then earn the MDiv (Master of Divinity) degree in an additional three years as part of preparation for ordination.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Fine Arts (BFA) degree is a specialized degree awarded for courses of study in the fine arts, frequently by an arts school or conservatory, although it is equally available at a significant number of traditional colleges and universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, the Bachelor of Fine Arts degree differs from a Bachelor of Arts degree in that the majority of the program consists of a practical studio component, as contrasted with lecture and discussion classes.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A typical BFA program in the United States consists of two-thirds study in the arts, with one-third in more general liberal arts studies.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] For a BA in art, the ratio might be reversed.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Film and Television (BFTV) degree is an undergraduate degree for the study of film and television production including areas of cinematography, directing, film production, script writing, sound, screenwriting, animation, and typography.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Integrated Studies (BIS) is an interdisciplinary bachelor's degree offered by several universities in the United States and Canada.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It allows students to design a customized and specific course of study to best suit their educational and professional objectives.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, this degree is sponsored by two or more departments within the university.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Journalism (BAJ or BScJ) degree is a professional degree awarded to students who have studied journalism at a four-year accredited university.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Not all universities, however, grant this degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In the United States, schools tend to offer the BA or BS with a major in journalism instead.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The world's oldest school of journalism at the University of Missouri offers a BJ degree, not to be confused with the bachelor's degree in jurisprudence at Oxford University.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In South Africa, Rhodes University has the oldest school of journalism in Africa and allows students to take a fourth-year specialisation to raise their BA to BAJ status, equivalent to a BA (Hons).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Landscape Architecture (BLA) degree is awarded to students who complete the five- (in some countries four-) year course of study in the field.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Professional Studies is awarded to students who major in professional career studies.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Library Science or Bachelor of Library and Information Science (BLSc, BLISc) degree is sometimes awarded to students who major in library science, although Master of Library Science degrees are more common.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Music (BMus) degree is a professional or academic undergraduate degree in music at most conservatories in the US and the UK.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is also commonly awarded at schools of music in large private or public universities.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Areas of study typically include music performance, music education, music therapy, music composition, academic fields (music history/musicology, music theory, ethnomusicology), and may include jazz, commercial music, recording technology, sacred music/music ministry, or music business.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Small liberal arts colleges and universities without schools of music often award only BA in music, with different sets of requirements.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A Bachelor of Nonprofit and Nongovernmental Organization Studies is a field that focuses on practices of the nonprofit sector.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] A variety of higher education institutions and research organizations are dedicated to the teaching and research of issues related to the nonprofit sector.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Additionally, individual courses within related disciplines (e.g.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Business, Sociology, Public Policy) examine nonprofit studies in a variety of contexts.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Nonprofit studies may also refer to studies of the voluntary sector, third sector, nongovernmental organizations, or civil society.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Mortuary Science (BMS) is a professional undergraduate degree, awarded by the Cincinnati College of Mortuary Science of Cincinnati, Ohio and Southern Illinois University Carbondale.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It was introduced in 1986 and it is awarded to students that complete 120 semester hours of course work and receive passing scores on the National Board Exam administered by The International Conference of Funeral Service Examining Boards.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Philosophy (BPhil. or PhB) degree is either an undergraduate or graduate degree (MPhil).
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, it entails independent research or a thesis/capstone project.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Variants include the Bachelor of Arts in Applied Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Clinical Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Forensic Psychology, Bachelor of Arts in Organizational Psychology.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Courses typically last four years, but may be as long as six.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Education degree (BEd) is a four-year undergraduate professional degree offered by many American colleges and universities for those preparing to be licensed as teachers.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Variants include the BEd, BAEd, BAT (Bachelor of Arts for Teaching), and BST degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Preparation for the MS in education, this degree is most often received by those interested in early childhood, elementary level, and special education, or by those planning to be school administrators.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Secondary level teachers often major in their subject area instead (i.e., history, chemistry, or mathematics), with a minor in education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some states require elementary teachers to choose a subject major as well, and minor in education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Some universities also offer concurrent, five-year programs with student completing both a bachelor's degree in arts or science as well as their BEd.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The possession of a BEd and a second bachelor's degree is required to teach in most public anglophone and francophone schools in Canada.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The BEd prepares teachers for completion of either MA (Master of Arts) programs in education, MEd (Master of Education) programs, or postgraduate certificates in education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science and/with Education degree (BScEd) is a degree awarded to students who complete the four- to five-year course of study in the field of science (major and minor in general biology, chemistry, physics, and mathematics) and education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Although notionally BSc and BEd are two degrees, they must be taken together.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The graduates will work as science (physics, chemistry, biology) teachers in high schools, as lecturers in pre university colleges and matriculation centers and can progress to postgraduate programs (MSc and PhD) in various areas in science or education.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in forestry (BScF) is a degree awarded to students who complete a three-year course of study in the field of forestry.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science degrees (BSc, ScB) along with the Bachelor of Arts degrees are the most common undergraduate degrees given.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Science in Law degree (BScL) is a special-purpose degree that allows someone who has had some prior studies but has not achieved a bachelor's degree to resume his or her education and take up the study of law with the goal of eventually receiving the juris doctor degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Social Work (BSW) degree is a four-year undergraduate degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Usually the first two years consist of liberal arts courses and the last two years focus on social work classes in human development, policy/law, research, and practice.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programs accredited by the Council on Social Work Education require BSW students to complete a minimum of 400 field education or internship hours.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Accredited BSW programs often allow students who are interested in obtaining a Master of Social Work degree to complete the degree in a shorter amount of time or waive courses.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] In Latin America, this is a four to five-year degree that can replace liberal arts subjects into health sciences, resulting in social work as a type of community psychology and socioeconomic studies, focused in hospitals, prisons, or pedagogy, among others.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Technology degree (BTech) is a three- or four-year undergraduate degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Generally, the program is comparable to a Bachelor of Science degree program, which is additionally supplemented by either occupational placements (supervised practical or internships) or practice-based classroom courses.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Laws (LLB) is the principal academic degree in law in most common law countries other than the United States, and anglophone Canada, where it has been superseded by the juris doctor (JD) degree.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Talmudic Law degree (BTL) or a First Talmudic Degree (FTD) is the degree awarded in most Yeshivas around the United States.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The course would have an interdisciplinary approach with a vast range of units so the tourismologist professional would be able to identify necessary actions toward a sustainable touristic environment focus on local community uniqueness, values and traditions.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] As tourism is a growing industry, in India there is a lot of opportunity for those who complete this course of study.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] It is available in select universities of India.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Mathematics or Bachelor of Mathematical Sciences degree (BMath and BMathSc) is given at the conclusion of a four-year honours program or a three-year general program.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Several universities, mostly in Canada and Australia, award such degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The usual degree for mathematics in all other countries is the BSc.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Urban and Regional Planning or Bachelor of Urban Planning or just Bachelor of Planning degree (BURP, BUP, or BPlan) is a degree offered at some institutions as a four or five-year professional undergraduate degree in urban planning.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] Programs vary in their focus on studio work and may or may not involve professional practice.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The Bachelor of Innovation is a four-year degree in a range of different fields.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The major fields, in engineering, business, arts, science or education, are similar to their associated BA or BSc degrees.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The general education elements are restructured to provide a common core of innovation, entrepreneurship and team skills.
[src:gail-ashley/bachelor-s-degree-p04] The degree was created as a direct response to the increasing pace of innovation in today's society and the need for graduates that understanding effective teaming, as well as the innovation process.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] The critical zone is an interdisciplinary field of research exploring the interactions among the land surface, vegetation, and water bodies, and extends through the pedosphere, unsaturated vadose zone, and saturated groundwater zone.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] Critical Zone science is the integration of Earth surface processes (such as landscape evolution, weathering, hydrology, geochemistry, and ecology) at multiple spatial and temporal scales and across anthropogenic gradients.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] These processes impact mass and energy exchange necessary for biomass productivity, chemical cycling, and water storage.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] The critical zone is studied at Critical Zone Observatories, where multiple scientific communities study various aspects of the critical zone that can lead to synthesized understanding of complex systems.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] Dimitrios Tsakalotos first introduced the term *critical zone* in chemistry literature in 1909 to describe the binary mixture of two fluids, but has since been adopted to refer to the "connection of vegetation to soil and weathered materials" by Gail Ashley in 1998.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] In October 2003, scientists attended the first Weathering System Science Workshop.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] Participants agreed to promote outreach activities to broaden the profile of involved Earth scientists and crafted a set of questions that would drive further development of Weathering System Science.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] This field of science was considered to include all aspects of chemistry, biology, physics, and geology of the critical zone.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] The Weathering System Science Consortium was established in early 2004 and later was changed to the Critical Zone Exploration Network (CZEN) in 2006.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] In October 2005 WSSC/CZEN solicitated a call for proposals to initiate seed sites that would help grow and establish a critical zone network.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] In total, ten sites have been awarded grants, and nine sites have received continued funding.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] In 2005, the University of Delaware hosted an NSF-sponsored workshop that resulted in a call by scientists for an international initiative to study the critical zone.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] A booklet, *Frontiers in Exploration of the Critical Zone*, was produced from the meeting.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] On July 24, 2006 NSF posted a solicitation for proposals for Critical Zone Observatories (CZO) within the Division of Earth Sciences.
[src:gail-ashley/earth-s-critical-zone] DENIN fosters a culture of scholarship that leverages the combined talents of affiliates and fellows through collaborative working groups, joint proposal development and, where synergistic, project resource coordination.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] Ashley was born Gail Mowry in Leominster, Massachusetts, on January 29, 1941.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] Her interest in geology developed at a young age under the tutelage of a neighbor and professor of geology.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] She earned a bachelor's degree in 1963 and a master's degree in 1972, both in geology, from the University of Massachusetts, Amherst.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] In 1977 Ashley received a Ph.D. from the University of British Columbia for research on sediment transport in tidal rivers.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] In 1977, Ashley was hired at Rutgers University, where she currently serves as a full professor.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] She has served as editor for several journals, including as the first female editor of the *Journal of Sedimentary Research* and the Geological Society of America Bulletin.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] She presented a lecture on "The Paleoclimate Framework of Human Evolution, Lessons from Olduvai Gorge, Tanzania" at Rutgers, publicized by WISE (Women in Scientific Education) in 2014.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] Ashley's research career has focused on glaciation and paleoecology.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] In 1998, she first introduced the term Critical Zone in Earth sciences to describe this thin zone of complex interactions involving rock, soil, water, air, and living organisms.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] From 1991 to 1992, Ashley was the president of the Society of Economic Paleontologists and Mineralogists and chaired the Northeast Section of the Geological Society of America (GSA).
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] She is active in the Association for Women Geoscientists to bring more women into scientific fields.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] From 1998 to 1999, she presided over the GSA and was the second female president in its history.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] From 1998 to 2002 she served as vice president of the International Association of Sedimentologists.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] In 2012, Ashley was the recipient of the GSA's Laurence L.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] Sloss Award for lifetime achievements and in 2020 received the GSA Limnogeology Division Israel C.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] Ashley has two children with her first husband, Stuart Ashley.
[src:gail-ashley/gail-ashley] She is currently married to Jeremy Delaney.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america-bulletin] The ***Geological Society of America Bulletin*** (until 1960 called ***The Bulletin of the Geological Society of America*** and also commonly referred to as ***GSA Bulletin***) is a peer-reviewed scientific journal that has been published by the Geological Society of America since 1890.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america-bulletin] Its first editor was William John McGee.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america-bulletin] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2016 impact factor of 4.212.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] The **Geological Society of America** (**GSA**) is a nonprofit organization dedicated to the advancement of the geosciences.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] The society was founded in Ithaca, New York, in 1888 by Alexander Winchell, John J.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] Procter and Edward Orton and has been headquartered at 3300 Penrose Place, Boulder, Colorado, US, since 1967.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] GSA began with 100 members under its first president, James Hall.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] In 1889 Mary Emilie Holmes became its first female member.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] It grew slowly but steadily to 600 members until 1931, when a nearly $4 million endowment from 1930 president R.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] As of December 2017, GSA had more than 25,000 members in over 100 countries.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] The society has six regional sections in North America, three interdisciplinary interest groups, and eighteen specialty divisions.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] The stated mission of GSA is "to advance geoscience research and discovery, service to society, stewardship of Earth, and the geosciences profession".
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] Its main activities are sponsoring scientific meetings and publishing scientific literature, particularly the peer-reviewed journals *Geological Society of America Bulletin*, published continuously since 1889, and *Geology*, published since 1973.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] In 2005, GSA introduced its online-only journal *Geosphere*, and in February 2009, GSA began publishing *Lithosphere* (both also peer-reviewed).
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] *Geosphere* and *Lithosphere* are open access as of 2018.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] GSA's monthly news and science magazine, *GSA Today*, is also open access online.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] GSA also publishes three book series: *Special Papers*, *Memoirs*, and *Field Guides*.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] A third major activity is awarding research grants to graduate students.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] GSA issues Position Statements "in support of and consistent with the GSA's Vision and Mission to develop consensus on significant professional, technical, and societal issues of relevance to the geosciences community.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] The Geological Society of America (GSA) supports the scientific conclusions that Earth's climate is changing; the climate changes are due in part to human activities; and the probable consequences of the climate changes will be significant and blind to geopolitical boundaries.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] Furthermore, the potential implications of global climate change and the time scale over which such changes will likely occur require active, effective, long-term planning.
[src:gail-ashley/geological-society-of-america] While the precise magnitude and rate of climate change cannot be predicted with absolute certainty, significant change will affect the planet and stress its inhabitants.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geology describes the structure of the Earth on and beneath its surface and the processes that have shaped that structure.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists study the mineralogical composition of rocks in order to get insight into their history of formation.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geology determines the relative ages of rocks found at a given location; geochemistry (a branch of geology) determines their absolute ages.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] By combining various petrological, crystallographic, and paleontological tools, geologists are able to chronicle the geological history of the Earth as a whole.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] One aspect is to demonstrate the age of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geology provides evidence for plate tectonics, the evolutionary history of life, and the Earth's past climates.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists broadly study the properties and processes of Earth and other terrestrial planets.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists use a wide variety of methods to understand the Earth's structure and evolution, including fieldwork, rock description, geophysical techniques, chemical analysis, physical experiments, and numerical modelling.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In practical terms, geology is important for mineral and hydrocarbon exploration and exploitation, evaluating water resources, understanding natural hazards, remediating environmental problems, and providing insights into past climate change.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geology is a major academic discipline, and it is central to geological engineering and plays an important role in geotechnical engineering.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The majority of geological data comes from research on solid Earth materials.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Meteorites and other extraterrestrial natural materials are also studied by geological methods.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Minerals are naturally occurring elements and compounds with a definite homogeneous chemical composition and an ordered atomic arrangement.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Amorphous substances that resemble a mineral are sometimes referred to as mineraloids, although there are exceptions such as georgeite and autunite.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Some amorphous substances formed by geological processes are considered minerals if the original substance was a mineral before metamictisation.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Each mineral has distinct physical properties, and there are many tests to determine each of them.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Minerals are often identified through these tests.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] A rock is any naturally occurring solid mass or aggregate of minerals or mineraloids.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Most research in geology is associated with the study of rocks, as they provide the primary record of the majority of the geological history of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] There are three major types of rock: igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The rock cycle illustrates the relationships among them (see diagram).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] When a rock solidifies or crystallizes from melt (magma or lava), it is an igneous rock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The active flow of molten rock is closely studied in volcanology, and igneous petrology aims to determine the history of igneous rocks from their original molten source to their final crystallization.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Rocks can be weathered and eroded, then redeposited and lithified into a sedimentary rock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Sedimentary rocks are mainly divided into four categories: sandstone, shale, carbonate, and evaporite.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This group of classifications focuses partly on the size of sedimentary particles (sandstone and shale), and partly on mineralogy and formation processes (carbonation and evaporation).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Igneous and sedimentary rocks can then be turned into metamorphic rocks by heat and pressure that change its mineral content, resulting in a characteristic fabric.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] All three types may melt again, and when this happens, new magma is formed, from which an igneous rock may once again solidify.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Organic matter, such as coal, bitumen, oil, and natural gas, is linked mainly to organic-rich sedimentary rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] To study all three types of rock, geologists evaluate the minerals of which they are composed and their other physical properties, such as texture and fabric.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists study unlithified materials (referred to as *superficial deposits*) that lie above the bedrock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This study is often known as Quaternary geology, after the Quaternary period of geologic history, which is the most recent period of geologic time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the 1960s, it was discovered that the Earth's lithosphere, which includes the crust and rigid uppermost portion of the upper mantle, is separated into tectonic plates that move across the plastically deforming, solid, upper mantle, which is called the asthenosphere.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This theory is supported by several types of observations, including seafloor spreading and the global distribution of mountain terrain and seismicity.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] There is an intimate coupling between the movement of the plates on the surface and the convection of the mantle (that is, the heat transfer caused by the slow movement of ductile mantle rock).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Thus, oceanic parts of plates and the adjoining mantle convection currents always move in the same direction – because the oceanic lithosphere is actually the rigid upper thermal boundary layer of the convecting mantle.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This coupling between rigid plates moving on the surface of the Earth and the convecting mantle is called plate tectonics.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The development of plate tectonics has provided a physical basis for many observations of the solid Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Plate tectonics has provided a mechanism for Alfred Wegener's theory of continental drift, in which the continents move across the surface of the Earth over geological time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] They provided a driving force for crustal deformation, and a new setting for the observations of structural geology.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The power of the theory of plate tectonics lies in its ability to combine all of these observations into a single theory of how the lithosphere moves over the convecting mantle, forming a "grand unifying theory of geology".
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Advances in seismology, computer modeling, and mineralogy and crystallography at high temperatures and pressures give insights into the internal composition and structure of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Seismologists can use the arrival times of seismic waves to image the interior of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Early advances in this field showed the existence of a liquid outer core (where shear waves were not able to propagate) and a dense solid inner core.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These advances led to the development of a layered model of the Earth, with a lithosphere (including crust) on top, the mantle below (separated within itself by seismic discontinuities at 410 and 660 kilometers), and the outer core and inner core below that.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Starting in the 1970s, seismologists have been able to use new techniques such as seismic full-waveform inversion to create detailed images of wave speeds inside the earth in the same way a doctor images a body in a CT scan.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These images have led to a much more detailed view of the interior of the Earth, and have replaced the simplified layered model with a much more dynamic model.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Mineralogists have been able to use the pressure and temperature data from the seismic and modeling studies alongside knowledge of the elemental composition of the Earth to reproduce these conditions in experimental settings and measure changes within the crystal structure.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These studies explain the chemical changes associated with the major seismic discontinuities in the mantle and show the crystallographic structures expected in the inner core of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The geological time scale encompasses the history of the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] It is bracketed at the earliest by the dates of the first Solar System material at 4.567 Ga (or 4.567 billion years ago) and the formation of the Earth at 4.54 Ga (4.54 billion years), which is the beginning of the Hadean eon – a division of geological time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] At the later end of the scale, it is marked by the present day (in the Holocene epoch).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The following five timelines show the geologic time scale to scale.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The first shows the entire time from the formation of Earth to the present, but this gives little space for the most recent eon.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The second timeline shows an expanded view of the most recent eon.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In a similar way, the most recent era is expanded in the third timeline, the most recent period is expanded in the fourth timeline, and the most recent epoch is expanded in the fifth timeline.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The epochs of lunar history are based on the chronology of impact events, and they are named after defining major impacts.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Hence, the Imbrian is named after the formation of the Mare Imbrium basin.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The ages of older lunar basins can be dated based on the strength of their intrinsic magnetic field, since the early Moon had a magnetic field that faded over time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The ages of craters can be estimated by morphological and stratigraphic classifications, with younger craters overlapping older impacts and generally showing less impact wear.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Methods for relative dating were developed when geology first emerged as a natural science.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists still use the following principles today as a means to provide information about geological history and the timing of geological events.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of uniformitarianism* states that the geological processes observed in operation that modify the Earth's crust at present have worked in much the same way over geological time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of intrusive relationships* concerns crosscutting intrusions.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In geology, when an igneous intrusion cuts across a formation of sedimentary rock, it can be determined that the igneous intrusion is younger than the sedimentary rock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Different types of intrusions include stocks, laccoliths, batholiths, sills and dikes.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of cross-cutting relationships* pertains to the formation of faults and the age of the sequences through which they cut.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Faults are younger than the rocks they cut; accordingly, if a fault is found that penetrates some formations but not those on top of it, then the formations that were cut are older than the fault, and the ones that are not cut must be younger than the fault.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Finding the key bed in these situations may help determine whether the fault is a normal fault or a thrust fault.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of inclusions and components* states that, with sedimentary rocks, if inclusions (or *clasts*) are found in a formation, then the inclusions must be older than the formation that contains them.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] For example, in sedimentary rocks, it is common for gravel from an older formation to be ripped up and included in a newer layer.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] A similar situation with igneous rocks occurs when xenoliths are found.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These foreign bodies are picked up as magma or lava flows, and are incorporated, later to cool in the matrix.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] As a result, xenoliths are older than the rock that contains them.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of original horizontality* states that the deposition of sediments occurs as essentially horizontal beds.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Observation of modern marine and non-marine sediments in a wide variety of environments supports this generalization (although cross-bedding is inclined, the overall orientation of cross-bedded units is horizontal).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of superposition* states that a sedimentary rock layer in a tectonically undisturbed sequence is younger than the one beneath it and older than the one above it.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Logically a younger layer cannot slip beneath a layer previously deposited.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This principle allows sedimentary layers to be viewed as a form of the vertical timeline, a partial or complete record of the time elapsed from deposition of the lowest layer to deposition of the highest bed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The *principle of faunal succession* is based on the appearance of fossils in sedimentary rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] As organisms exist during the same period throughout the world, their presence or (sometimes) absence provides a relative age of the formations where they appear.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Based on principles that William Smith laid out almost a hundred years before the publication of Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the principles of succession developed independently of evolutionary thought.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The principle becomes quite complex, however, given the uncertainties of fossilization, localization of fossil types due to lateral changes in habitat (facies change in sedimentary strata), and that not all fossils formed globally at the same time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists use methods to determine the absolute age of rock samples and geological events.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These may be used in conjunction with relative dating methods or to calibrate relative methods.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] At the beginning of the 20th century, advancement in geological science was facilitated by the ability to obtain accurate absolute dates to geological events using radioactive isotopes and other methods.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This changed the understanding of geological time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Previously, geologists could only use fossils and stratigraphic correlation to date sections of rock relative to one another.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] With isotopic dates, it became possible to assign absolute ages to rock units, and these absolute dates could be applied to fossil sequences in which there was datable material, converting the old relative ages into new absolute ages.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These are used in geochronologic and thermochronologic studies.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The most suitable isotope systems for this purpose include uranium–lead, rubidium–strontium, and potassium–argon.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Uranium–thorium dating is used for dating calcium-carbonate.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Dating of lava and volcanic ash layers found within a stratigraphic sequence can provide absolute age data for sedimentary rock units that do not contain radioactive isotopes and calibrate relative dating techniques.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These methods can be used to determine ages of pluton emplacement.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Fractionation of the lanthanide series elements is used to compute ages since rocks were removed from the mantle.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Other methods are used for more recent events.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Optically stimulated luminescence and cosmogenic radionuclide dating are used to date surfaces and/or erosion rates.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Dendrochronology can be used for the dating of landscapes.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Radiocarbon dating is used for geologically young materials containing organic carbon.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Thermochemical techniques can be used to determine temperature profiles within the crust, the uplift of mountain ranges, and paleo-topography.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The geology of an area changes through time as rock units are deposited and inserted, and deformational processes alter their shapes and locations.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Rock units are first emplaced either by deposition onto the surface or intrusion into the overlying rock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Deposition can occur when sediments settle onto the surface of the Earth and later lithify into sedimentary rock, or when as volcanic material such as volcanic ash or lava flows blanket the surface.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Igneous intrusions such as batholiths, laccoliths, dikes, and sills, push upwards into the overlying rock, and crystallize as they intrude.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] After the initial sequence of rocks has been deposited, the rock units can be deformed and/or metamorphosed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Deformation typically occurs as a result of horizontal shortening, horizontal extension, or side-to-side (strike-slip) motion.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These structural regimes broadly relate to convergent boundaries, divergent boundaries, and transform boundaries, respectively, between tectonic plates.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] When rock units are placed under horizontal compression, they shorten and become thicker.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Because rock units, other than muds, do not significantly change in volume, this is accomplished in two primary ways: through faulting and folding.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the shallow crust, where brittle deformation can occur, thrust faults form, which causes the deeper rock to move on top of the shallower rock.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Because deeper rock is often older, as noted by the principle of superposition, this can result in older rocks moving on top of younger ones.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Movement along faults can result in folding, either because the faults are not planar or because rock layers are dragged along, forming drag folds as slip occurs along the fault.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Deeper in the Earth, rocks behave plastically and fold instead of faulting.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These folds can either be those where the material in the center of the fold buckles upwards, creating "antiforms", or where it buckles downwards, creating "synforms".
[src:gail-ashley/geology] If the tops of the rock units within the folds remain pointing upwards, they are called anticlines and synclines, respectively.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] If some of the units in the fold are facing downward, the structure is called an overturned anticline or syncline, and if all of the rock units are overturned or the correct up-direction is unknown, they are simply called by the most general terms, antiforms, and synforms.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Even higher pressures and temperatures during horizontal shortening can cause both folding and metamorphism of the rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This metamorphism causes changes in the mineral composition of the rocks; creates a foliation, or planar surface, that is related to mineral growth under stress.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This can remove signs of the original textures of the rocks, such as bedding in sedimentary rocks, flow features of lavas, and crystal patterns in crystalline rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Extension causes the rock units as a whole to become longer and thinner.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This is primarily accomplished through normal faulting and through the ductile stretching and thinning.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Normal faults drop rock units that are higher below those that are lower.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This typically results in younger units ending up below older units.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Stretching of units can result in their thinning.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In fact, at one location within the Maria Fold and Thrust Belt, the entire sedimentary sequence of the Grand Canyon appears over a length of less than a meter.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Rocks at the depth to be ductilely stretched are often metamorphosed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These stretched rocks can pinch into lenses, known as *boudins*, after the French word for "sausage" because of their visual similarity.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Where rock units slide past one another, strike-slip faults develop in shallow regions, and become shear zones at deeper depths where the rocks deform ductilely.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The addition of new rock units, both depositionally and intrusively, often occurs during deformation.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Faulting and other deformational processes result in the creation of topographic gradients, causing material on the rock unit that is increasing in elevation to be eroded by hillslopes and channels.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These sediments are deposited on the rock unit that is going down.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Continual motion along the fault maintains the topographic gradient in spite of the movement of sediment and continues to create accommodation space for the material to deposit.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Deformational events are often associated with volcanism and igneous activity.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Volcanic ashes and lavas accumulate on the surface, and igneous intrusions enter from below.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Dikes, long, planar igneous intrusions, enter along cracks, and therefore often form in large numbers in areas that are being actively deformed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This can result in the emplacement of dike swarms, such as those that are observable across the Canadian shield, or rings of dikes around the lava tube of a volcano.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] All of these processes do not necessarily occur in a single environment and do not necessarily occur in a single order.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The Hawaiian Islands, for example, consist almost entirely of layered basaltic lava flows.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The sedimentary sequences of the mid-continental United States and the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States contain almost-undeformed stacks of sedimentary rocks that have remained in place since Cambrian time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Other areas are much more geologically complex.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the southwestern United States, sedimentary, volcanic, and intrusive rocks have been metamorphosed, faulted, foliated, and folded.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Even older rocks, such as the Acasta gneiss of the Slave craton in northwestern Canada, the oldest known rock in the world have been metamorphosed to the point where their origin is indiscernible without laboratory analysis.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In many places, the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States being a very visible example, the lower rock units were metamorphosed and deformed, and then deformation ended and the upper, undeformed units were deposited.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Although any amount of rock emplacement and rock deformation can occur, and they can occur any number of times, these concepts provide a guide to understanding the geological history of an area.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists use a number of fields, laboratory, and numerical modeling methods to decipher Earth history and to understand the processes that occur on and inside the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In typical geological investigations, geologists use primary information related to petrology (the study of rocks), stratigraphy (the study of sedimentary layers), and structural geology (the study of positions of rock units and their deformation).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In many cases, geologists study modern soils, rivers, landscapes, and glaciers; investigate past and current life and biogeochemical pathways, and use geophysical methods to investigate the subsurface.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Sub-specialities of geology may distinguish *endogenous* and *exogenous* geology.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geological field work varies depending on the task at hand.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] , thin sections are used to study rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The method is based on the distinct refractive indexes of different minerals.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In addition to identifying rocks in the field (lithology), petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through optical microscopy (such as with the petrographic microscope) and by using an electron microprobe.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Petrologists can use fluid inclusion data and perform high temperature and pressure physical experiments to understand the temperatures and pressures at which different mineral phases appear, and how they change through igneous and metamorphic processes.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This research can be extrapolated to the field to understand metamorphic processes and the conditions of crystallization of igneous rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This work can help to explain processes that occur within the Earth, such as subduction and magma chamber evolution.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geological samples to observe the fabric within the rocks, which gives information about strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] They plot and combine measurements of geological structures to better understand the orientations of faults and folds to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In addition, they perform analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The analysis of structures is often accomplished by plotting the orientations of various features onto stereonets.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] A stereonet is a stereographic projection of a sphere onto a plane, in which planes are projected as lines and lines are projected as points.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These can be used to find the locations of fold axes, relationships between faults, and relationships between other geological structures.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Among the most well-known experiments in structural geology are those involving orogenic wedges, which are zones in which mountains are built along convergent tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the analog versions of these experiments, horizontal layers of sand are pulled along a lower surface into a back stop, which results in realistic-looking patterns of faulting and the growth of a critically tapered (all angles remain the same) orogenic wedge.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Numerical models work in the same way as these analog models, though they are often more sophisticated and can include patterns of erosion and uplift in the mountain belt.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This helps to show the relationship between erosion and the shape of a mountain range.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These studies can give useful information about pathways for metamorphism through pressure, temperature, space, and time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the laboratory, stratigraphers analyze samples of stratigraphic sections that can be returned from the field, such as those from drill cores.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Stratigraphers analyze data from geophysical surveys that show the locations of stratigraphic units in the subsurface.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geophysical data and well logs can be combined to produce a better view of the subsurface, and stratigraphers often use computer programs to do this in three dimensions.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Stratigraphers can then use these data to reconstruct ancient processes occurring on the surface of the Earth, interpret past environments, and locate areas for water, coal, and hydrocarbon extraction.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the laboratory, biostratigraphers analyze rock samples from outcrop and drill cores for the fossils found in them.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These fossils help scientists to date the core and to understand the depositional environment in which the rock units formed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geochronologists precisely date rocks within the stratigraphic section to provide better absolute bounds on the timing and rates of deposition.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Magnetic stratigraphers look for signs of magnetic reversals in igneous rock units within the drill cores.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Other scientists perform stable-isotope studies on the rocks to gain information about past climate.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] With the advent of space exploration in the twentieth century, geologists have begun to look at other planetary bodies in the same ways that have been developed to study the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This new field of study is called planetary geology (sometimes known as astrogeology) and relies on known geological principles to study other bodies of the Solar System.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This is a major aspect of planetary science, and largely focuses on the terrestrial planets, icy moons, asteroids, comets, and meteorites.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] However, some planetary geophysicists study the giant planets and exoplanets.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Although the Greek-language-origin prefix *geo* refers to Earth, "geology" is often used in conjunction with the names of other planetary bodies when describing their composition and internal processes: examples are "the geology of Mars" and "Lunar geology".
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Specialized terms such as *selenology* (studies of the Moon), *areology* (of Mars), *hermesology* (of Mercury), etc., are also in use.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Although planetary geologists are interested in studying all aspects of other planets, a significant focus is to search for evidence of past or present life on other worlds.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This has led to many missions whose primary or ancillary purpose is to examine planetary bodies for evidence of life.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] One of these is the Phoenix lander, which analyzed Martian polar soil for water, chemical, and mineralogical constituents related to biological processes.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Economic geology is a branch of geology that deals with aspects of economic minerals that humankind uses to fulfill various needs.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Economic minerals are those extracted profitably for various practical uses.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Economic geologists help locate and manage the Earth's natural resources, such as petroleum and coal, as well as mineral resources, which include metals such as iron, copper, and uranium.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Mining geology consists of the extractions of mineral and ore resources from the Earth.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Some resources of economic interests include gemstones, metals such as gold and copper, and many industrial minerals such as asbestos, magnesite, perlite, mica, phosphates, zeolites, clay, silica, and pumice, as well as elements such as sulfur and helium.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Petroleum geologists study the locations of the subsurface of the Earth that can contain extractable hydrocarbons, especially petroleum and natural gas.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Because many of these reservoirs are found in sedimentary basins, they study the formation of these basins, their sedimentary and tectonic evolution, and the present-day positions of the rock units.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Engineering geology is the application of geological principles to engineering practice for the purpose of assuring that the geological factors affecting the location, design, construction, operation, and maintenance of engineering works are properly addressed.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Engineering geology is distinct from geological engineering, particularly in North America.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In the field of civil engineering, geological principles and analyses are used in order to ascertain the mechanical principles of the material on which structures are built.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This allows tunnels to be built without collapsing, bridges and skyscrapers to be built with sturdy foundations, and buildings to be built that will not settle in clay and mud.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geology and geological principles can be applied to various environmental problems such as stream restoration, the restoration of brownfields, and the understanding of the interaction between natural habitat and the geological environment.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Groundwater hydrology, or hydrogeology, is used to locate groundwater, which can often provide a ready supply of uncontaminated water and is especially important in arid regions, and to monitor the spread of contaminants in groundwater wells.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists obtain data through stratigraphy, boreholes, core samples, and ice cores.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Ice cores and sediment cores are used for paleoclimate reconstructions, which tell geologists about past and present temperature, precipitation, and sea level across the globe.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] These datasets are our primary source of information on global climate change outside of instrumental data.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Geologists and geophysicists study natural hazards in order to enact safe building codes and warning systems that are used to prevent loss of property and life.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The study of the physical material of the Earth dates back at least to ancient Greece when Theophrastus (372–287 BCE) wrote the work *Peri Lithon* (*On Stones*).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] During the Roman period, Pliny the Elder wrote in detail of the many minerals and metals, then in practical use – even correctly noting the origin of amber.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Additionally, in the 4th century BCE Aristotle made critical observations of the slow rate of geological change.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] He observed the composition of the land and formulated a theory where the Earth changes at a slow rate and that these changes cannot be observed during one person's lifetime.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Aristotle developed one of the first evidence-based concepts connected to the geological realm regarding the rate at which the Earth physically changes.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Abu al-Rayhan al-Biruni (973–1048 CE) was one of the earliest Persian geologists, whose works included the earliest writings on the geology of India, hypothesizing that the Indian subcontinent was once a sea.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Georgius Agricola (1494–1555) published his groundbreaking work *De Natura Fossilium* in 1546 and is seen as the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Nicolas Steno (1638–1686) is credited with the law of superposition, the principle of original horizontality, and the principle of lateral continuity: three defining principles of stratigraphy.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The word *geology* was first used by Ulisse Aldrovandi in 1603, then by Jean-André Deluc in 1778 and introduced as a fixed term by Horace-Bénédict de Saussure in 1779.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The word is derived from the Greek γῆ, *gê*, meaning "earth" and λόγος, *logos*, meaning "speech".
[src:gail-ashley/geology] But according to another source, the word "geology" comes from a Norwegian, Mikkel Pedersøn Escholt (1600–1669), who was a priest and scholar.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Escholt first used the definition in his book titled, *Geologia Norvegica* (1657).
[src:gail-ashley/geology] William Smith (1769–1839) drew some of the first geological maps and began the process of ordering rock strata (layers) by examining the fossils contained in them.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In 1763, Mikhail Lomonosov published his treatise *On the Strata of Earth*.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] His work was the first narrative of modern geology, based on the unity of processes in time and explanation of the Earth's past from the present.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] James Hutton (1726–1797) is often viewed as the first modern geologist.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In 1785 he presented a paper entitled *Theory of the Earth* to the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In his paper, he explained his theory that the Earth must be much older than had previously been supposed to allow enough time for mountains to be eroded and for sediments to form new rocks at the bottom of the sea, which in turn were raised up to become dry land.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Hutton published a two-volume version of his ideas in 1795.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The first geological map of the U.S. was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In 1807, Maclure commenced the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Almost every state in the Union was traversed and mapped by him, the Allegheny Mountains being crossed and recrossed some 50 times.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The results of his unaided labours were submitted to the American Philosophical Society in a memoir entitled *Observations on the Geology of the United States explanatory of a Geological Map*, and published in the *Society's Transactions*, together with the nation's first geological map.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This antedates William Smith's geological map of England by six years, although it was constructed using a different classification of rocks.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Sir Charles Lyell (1797–1875) first published his famous book, *Principles of Geology*, in 1830.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This book, which influenced the thought of Charles Darwin, successfully promoted the doctrine of uniformitarianism.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] This theory states that slow geological processes have occurred throughout the Earth's history and are still occurring today.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] In contrast, catastrophism is the theory that Earth's features formed in single, catastrophic events and remained unchanged thereafter.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Though Hutton believed in uniformitarianism, the idea was not widely accepted at the time.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Much of 19th-century geology revolved around the question of the Earth's exact age.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Estimates varied from a few hundred thousand to billions of years.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] By the early 20th century, radiometric dating allowed the Earth's age to be estimated at two billion years.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The awareness of this vast amount of time opened the door to new theories about the processes that shaped the planet.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Some of the most significant advances in 20th-century geology have been the development of the theory of plate tectonics in the 1960s and the refinement of estimates of the planet's age.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Plate tectonics theory arose from two separate geological observations: seafloor spreading and continental drift.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] The theory revolutionized the Earth sciences.
[src:gail-ashley/geology] Today the Earth is known to be approximately 4.5 billion years old.
